To Labor in Government

A calamity had taken place. A catastrophe. A car crash in slow motion.

It hadn’t started like this. Early in the night, the obvious states had come in. Alabama and New York had slotted into their obvious columns. The crowds at the George W. Bush Election Night Party inside the Reagan Building had watched as Republican and Democratic electoral votes grew higher and higher. They were there as the nation tiptoed to a precipice and then, at some point past 2:00 AM, flung itself off it. Though CNN, FOX, and MSNBC had refused to call it, the old fogeys at CBS had taken a bold step into the unknown—the election was tied 269-269. For the first time since 1800, the House of Representatives would pick the president.

The enormity of the event had not yet reached those gathered in the Reagan Building. Decked in their “W” hats and American flag-patterned outfits, they looked confused more than anything. George W. Bush could see them murmuring through a tiny monitor in his makeshift green room. They were growing anxious as word spread that his opponent was planning to address their own supporters within the next few minutes. His own silence was becoming noticeable, concerning, but he could not move himself to act. For the first time in a long time, he felt sapped of his certainty.

“Sir?”

George jumped at the sudden intrusion. He spun to see, not Rove, not his running mate, but Blake Gottesman—his bag man. The boy, gangly with spots of acne, shifted his weight from side to side like a child trying to hold in his bladder.

“Sorry for bothering, Mr. President, but um…” George became aware of a phone in the boy’s hand. His mind jumped between a dozen possibilities. “It’s your father. You told me to tell you if he called tonight?”

George blinked. Then, as if in a dream, he beckoned for the boy to approach and took the phone from him with a shaky hand. Blake took a step backward and then vanished from the green room as George took the call off hold.

“Hi Poppy,” said George. His voice seemed distant.

From thousands of miles away came the voice of George’s father, harsh and clipped. “I’ve been on the phone with Jeb. He’s been talking with his people and he thinks that ABC is right. This thing’s going for a tie or, at the very least, an extended recount.” There was a rumble that George recognized as a sigh. “This is worse than 2000. What a goddamn mess.”

“We don’t know that yet,” murmured George. His voice seemed strangely child-like, sullen. He had a brief flash of being back in elementary school, trying to explain his report card. “There’s still absentee ballots. There’s still military ballots, you know what I’m saying? There could be fraud. K-Karl says—.”

“Jesus Christ, listen to yourself. ‘Voter fraud.’” The voice was high-pitched, mocking. “Give me a break.”

“O-okay. Maybe there’s not fraud. Maybe… I mean, we don’t gotta resignate—. I mean, I we don’t have to resign ourselves to this. There’s gonna be a run-off. We could still win in the House. That’s what happens next, right? We can still come out on top.”

He was so desperate. If Poppy could just say one positive thing, if he could give him one reassurance, everything would be okay.

Instead, there was a long and deafening silence on the other end of the receiver. “No, George. The Democrats are probably going to win the House.” He let the sentence sit there, moldering. “They’ll get sworn in and then, on January 6th, they’ll vote down the line for the Democrat. You will lose. You will be evicted from the White House. There is no reprieve coming. Christ is not going to descend from the heavens to save you. Do you understand what I’m saying?”

He was quiet. He remembered how he’d come home to Poppy drunk one night when he was in his 30s. He remembered the disgusted look on his father’s face.

“Answer me when I talk to you. Do you understand?”

George swallowed. “Yeah… Poppy. I understand.”

“Good. Jeb and I will call you tomorrow about how we can play this, but what’s important right now is you get out there. You tell the people at the Reagan Center that these results are not what you wanted but you are following them closely and you will respect the will of the voters, whatever that may be. Do you understand?”

“Yeah.”

“Okay. Well, if you ever listened to me, you would have done this hours ago.” Poppy gave a huff. "Just get out there before things get any worse. Don’t forget, we’ll talk tomorrow.”

And then, without ceremony, Poppy hung up. Bush allowed himself to listen to the silence for several moments. Then, he reconstructed his smile. He pretended to be jovial as he walked through rows of sullen aides. He wrapped his arm around Laura and kissed her gently on the cheek, a gesture he’d seen his father do many times before. Then, he stepped out onto the stage before the crowd. He could hear their voices but, with the stage lights blaring, he could not see their faces.

No Greater Privilege

The excitement had been building for hours inside the Reagan Building in downtown DC. First, the noncompetitive states had come in—Alabama, South Carolina, Utah—inspiring mild cheers from their partisans. Then, there’d been a raft of Republican-leaning states. These had been no great surprises; there were no stunning upsets from what the forecasters had predicted. Still, their number had steadily grown—173 to 188 to 191. The crowds had watched the screens at his Election Night party, bouncing between despair and anticipation, until finally, after midnight, CNN called it. There were still votes to be counted, but according to their projections: George W. Bush had avoided defeat. A cheer went up through the building.

He could hear their shouts echoing through the building, but the sensation George felt in his makeshift green room was exhaustion. It had been a hard four years and an even harder campaign. His body felt ragged, overused. He imagined himself as a rag doll struggling itself stitched together after weeks of being jerked around.

George was aware of a shape standing in the door. He turned and saw his personal assistant, a beanpole of a man, holding a cell phone. He forced himself to smile. “Hey, Blake, is that there the rebels calling to offer their surrender?”

His wry tone flew over the boy’s head. “Uh, no. I, uh, was able to get through to President Bush like you—. I mean, I was able to get through to your father. I know you’d wanted to talk to him before…”

George offered some vague Texan platitude, took the phone, and ushered the boy away. Then, he took a breath and took the call off hold. “Heya, Poppy. Glad you stayed up.”

There was the sound of breathing on the other end. A hand setting a glass on a coaster. “Your mother went to bed, but I’ve been talking to Jeb.” A pause as the voice on the other end took another sip of his drink. “He’ll probably want to call you when things settle down.”

“Oh!” He dulled his intelligence, willed himself to be more dense. “Well, I’ll be looking forward to that. I really will.” He wandered around the green room, busying himself by adjusting make-up bottles and peering into the tiny monitor that displayed the happy crowds in the atrium. They were playing some country song now to fill the time, something by Toby Keith. “Pretty big night. Good for everyone.”

“I suppose you managed to clear the bar and win an election.”

“Yeah, yeah… It’s gonna be a real game change from here on out, Poppy. No more having to worry about legacy, you know what I mean?” He continued staring into the tiny monitor. He wished they would cheer louder, make themselves heard to Poppy over the phone. “Things are gonna be different these next few years.”

There was a long pause. George was sure their call had been disconnected. Then, in a voice that mixed with the static came a low rumble. “No, George. It’s not.”

In the background, Toby Keith’s preening about family and country values suddenly seemed hollow and sarcastic. George gripped the phone hard.

“You’ve made your choices. There are no ‘new beginnings.’ There are no ‘fresh starts.’ You made your choices. You set this country down a path. By winning, all you did was guarantee that you’ll be the one dealing with the consequences of your actions. Nothing else.”

“Okay.”

“No one’s going to bail you out of your messes for you, Junior. This isn’t Yale.”

George was quiet and stared at his feet. He swallowed to bury the heavy feeling in his throat. “Hey, Poppy, I, uh, I got to go. The crowd out here is getting pretty rowdy and they’re tellin’ me I should give my victory speech before things get out of hand. Let’s talk about this stuff later, okay?”

There was an exasperated sigh through the receiver followed by the sound of someone downing the remainder of his bourbon. “Alright. Well, I should get to bed anyway. Don’t forget that Jeb will call you. We’ll talk more in the morning.”

“Okay, love you Poppy,” said George, only to be interrupted by the sound of the call disconnecting. He let the drone of the silent telephone bore into him. He allowed himself a few brief moments of quiet before putting back on his mask of cowboy confidence and exiting his room. He forced himself to emerge and greet his many smiling aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd in front of him but he could hear their voices.

George was aware of a shape standing in the door. He turned and saw his personal assistant, a beanpole of a man, holding a cell phone. He forced himself to smile. “Hey, Blake, is that there the rebels calling to offer their surrender?”

His wry tone flew over the boy’s head. “Uh, no. I, uh, was able to get through to President Bush like you—. I mean, I was able to get through to your father. I know you’d wanted to talk to him before…”

George offered some vague Texan platitude, took the phone, and ushered the boy away. Then, he took a breath and took the call off hold. “Heya, Poppy. Glad you stayed up.”

There was the sound of breathing on the other end. A hand setting a glass on a coaster. “Your mother went to bed, but I’ve been talking to Jeb.” A pause as the voice on the other end took another sip of his drink. “He’ll probably want to call you when things settle down.”

“Oh!” He dulled his intelligence, willed himself to be more dense. “Well, I’ll be looking forward to that. I really will.” He wandered around the green room, busying himself by adjusting make-up bottles and peering into the tiny monitor that displayed the happy crowds in the atrium. They were playing some country song now to fill the time, something by Toby Keith. “Pretty big night. Good for everyone.”

“I suppose you managed to clear the bar and win an election.”

“Yeah, yeah… It’s gonna be a real game change from here on out, Poppy. No more having to worry about legacy, you know what I mean?” He continued staring into the tiny monitor. He wished they would cheer louder, make themselves heard to Poppy over the phone. “Things are gonna be different these next few years.”

There was a long pause. George was sure their call had been disconnected. Then, in a voice that mixed with the static came a low rumble. “No, George. It’s not.”

In the background, Toby Keith’s preening about family and country values suddenly seemed hollow and sarcastic. George gripped the phone hard.

“You’ve made your choices. There are no ‘new beginnings.’ There are no ‘fresh starts.’ You made your choices. You set this country down a path. By winning, all you did was guarantee that you’ll be the one dealing with the consequences of your actions. Nothing else.”

“Okay.”

“No one’s going to bail you out of your messes for you, Junior. This isn’t Yale.”

George was quiet and stared at his feet. He swallowed to bury the heavy feeling in his throat. “Hey, Poppy, I, uh, I got to go. The crowd out here is getting pretty rowdy and they’re tellin’ me I should give my victory speech before things get out of hand. Let’s talk about this stuff later, okay?”

There was an exasperated sigh through the receiver followed by the sound of someone downing the remainder of his bourbon. “Alright. Well, I should get to bed anyway. Don’t forget that Jeb will call you. We’ll talk more in the morning.”

“Okay, love you Poppy,” said George, only to be interrupted by the sound of the call disconnecting. He let the drone of the silent telephone bore into him. He allowed himself a few brief moments of quiet before putting back on his mask of cowboy confidence and exiting his room. He forced himself to emerge and greet his many smiling aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd in front of him but he could hear their voices.

George was aware of a shape standing in the door. He turned and saw his personal assistant, a beanpole of a man, holding a cell phone. He forced himself to smile. “Hey, Blake, is that there the rebels calling to offer their surrender?”

His wry tone flew over the boy’s head. “Uh, no. I, uh, was able to get through to President Bush like you—. I mean, I was able to get through to your father. I know you’d wanted to talk to him before…”

George offered some vague Texan platitude, took the phone, and ushered the boy away. Then, he took a breath and took the call off hold. “Heya, Poppy. Glad you stayed up.”

There was the sound of breathing on the other end. A hand setting a glass on a coaster. “Your mother went to bed, but I’ve been talking to Jeb.” A pause as the voice on the other end took another sip of his drink. “He’ll probably want to call you when things settle down.”

“Oh!” He dulled his intelligence, willed himself to be more dense. “Well, I’ll be looking forward to that. I really will.” He wandered around the green room, busying himself by adjusting make-up bottles and peering into the tiny monitor that displayed the happy crowds in the atrium. They were playing some country song now to fill the time, something by Toby Keith. “Pretty big night. Good for everyone.”

“I suppose you managed to clear the bar and win an election.”

“Yeah, yeah… It’s gonna be a real game change from here on out, Poppy. No more having to worry about legacy, you know what I mean?” He continued staring into the tiny monitor. He wished they would cheer louder, make themselves heard to Poppy over the phone. “Things are gonna be different these next few years.”

There was a long pause. George was sure their call had been disconnected. Then, in a voice that mixed with the static came a low rumble. “No, George. It’s not.”

In the background, Toby Keith’s preening about family and country values suddenly seemed hollow and sarcastic. George gripped the phone hard.

“You’ve made your choices. There are no ‘new beginnings.’ There are no ‘fresh starts.’ You made your choices. You set this country down a path. By winning, all you did was guarantee that you’ll be the one dealing with the consequences of your actions. Nothing else.”

“Okay.”

“No one’s going to bail you out of your messes for you, Junior. This isn’t Yale.”

George was quiet and stared at his feet. He swallowed to bury the heavy feeling in his throat. “Hey, Poppy, I, uh, I got to go. The crowd out here is getting pretty rowdy and they’re tellin’ me I should give my victory speech before things get out of hand. Let’s talk about this stuff later, okay?”

There was an exasperated sigh through the receiver followed by the sound of someone downing the remainder of his bourbon. “Alright. Well, I should get to bed anyway. Don’t forget that Jeb will call you. We’ll talk more in the morning.”

“Okay, love you Poppy,” said George, only to be interrupted by the sound of the call disconnecting. He let the drone of the silent telephone bore into him. He allowed himself a few brief moments of quiet before putting back on his mask of cowboy confidence and exiting his room. He forced himself to emerge and greet his many smiling aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd in front of him but he could hear their voices.

No Greater Privilege

The excitement inside the Reagan building in downtown DC had been building in the hours before the polls closed. Republicans, decked in red baseball caps and pins and small American flags had descended on the building, excited to see just how badly they beat Robert Byrd. Bush campaign volunteers passed out popcorn while a projection of Fox’s Brit Hume intoned on rock-bottom Democratic turnout and the possibility of a historic outcome. New York could flip, so too could Hawaii. This could be the final, absurd defeat of the Democrat Party and the so-called anti-war movement, he informed the gleeful crowd.

Then, as the hours ticked by, air went out of the balloon. Yes, the president was on track to win victory, but it was not the historic victory they had been promised. The usual blue states slotted into their column, followed by a spattering of the Old South. At 2:00 AM, the networks called it. George W. Bush had won re-election over Robert Byrd. A cheer went up in the crowd. It sounded hollow.

In his green room, George watched a stream of the assembled people. He bit his lip as he focused on their forced smiles and awkward laughs. A campaign volunteer asked a woman to put away an enormous sign that read, “BUSH COUNTRY” and displayed the continental United States in crimson red.

“Sir?”

George turned away from the small television. Standing in the door frame stood his Blake, his bagman. George forced himself to give the boy a smile.

“Heya, Blake,” he said with faux-cheerfulness. In the corner of his eye, he could still see the teeming crowds. Was it his imagination, or did they look smaller than they had a few minutes prior? “Just getting myself pumped for my, uh, victory speech. What can I do you for?”

“Well, congratulations, sir. I, uh, don’t want to get in the way of your work.” Blake gave the president a smile that showed no teeth. Fear gripped him. Was Blake disappointed in him too? “But you asked me to get you if your father called. The former president, I mean.”

George ignored the icy chill on his back and made a dramatic gesture. “Of course! God, Poppy! Let’s see what the old bastard has to say, huh?”

Again, Blake gave a thin toothless smile. He removed a phone from his pocket and pressed it into George’s hand before exiting. There was a click as George took the call off hold.

“Heya, Poppy. Glad you stayed up.”

There was the sound of breathing on the other end. A hand setting a glass on a coaster. “Your mother went to bed hours ago, but I’ve been talking to Jeb.” A pause as the voice on the other end took another sip of his drink. “He’ll probably want to call you when things settle down.”

“Oh!” He dulled his intelligence, willed himself to be more dense. “Well, I’ll be looking forward to that. I really will.” He wandered around the green room, busying himself by adjusting make-up bottles. Anything to focus his gaze on something other than the stream of his rally. “Important to hear from the, uh, best and brightest for the next four years.”

Poppy gave a non-commital grunt. “If that’s what you think. Not the result I’d use to launch any big projects, but you never did follow my advice.”

“I won the election, Poppy.”

“Did you now? A bare victory against an out-of-touch geriatric… Robert Byrd… God.” ” George could almost see Poppy shaking his head. “You’re lucky they didn’t run a real candidate this year. God, if Clinton had run—.”

“I’d have beat her too,” George said, but for some reason his voice sounded whiny.

“If that’s what you say, but… don’t be surprised if the usual people on Capitol Hill aren’t taking your ‘mandate’ seriously. They smell blood in the water and no one’s gonna be able to bail you out.”

George was quiet and stared at his feet. He swallowed to bury the heavy feeling in his throat. “Hey, Poppy, I, uh, I got to go. The crowd out here is getting pretty rowdy and they’re tellin’ me I should give my victory speech before things get out of hand. Let’s talk about this stuff later, okay?”

There was an exasperated sigh through the receiver followed by the sound of someone downing the remainder of his bourbon. “Alright. Well, I should get to bed anyway. Don’t forget that Jeb will call you. We’ll talk more in the morning.”

“Okay, love you Poppy,” said George, only to be interrupted by the sound of the call disconnecting. He let the drone of the silent telephone bore into him. He allowed himself a few brief moments of quiet before putting back on his mask of cowboy confidence and exiting his room. He forced himself to emerge and greet his many aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd in front of him but he could hear their voices.

No Higher Honor

He could hear them chanting inside the Reagan Building’s atrium. He could feel the vibrations from their shouts and stomping as state after state turned a crimson red. “FOUR MORE YEARS! FOUR MORE YEARS!” Fox had called the race an hour ago, followed quickly by CNN. The haters at MSNBC still held out, sustained by half-memories of 2000 and delirious hopes regarding absentee ballots, but it wouldn’t be long until they too surrendered. He was certain of it. He took a swig of his non-alcoholic beer as the voices surged again. “FOUR MORE YEARS! FOUR MORE YEARS!”

He was aware of a hesitant knock on the door of his makeshift green room, but he did not turn. He was too busy luxuriating in the love of the crowd. He closed his eyes and imagined the liberals in Washington weeping and tearing out their hair. He imagined them throwing themselves off buildings.

“Sir?”

George stifled a frown and turned. Silhouetted against the doorway stood his bag man. His lips were tight and arms crossed. In one hand was a cell phone. At once, the energy of the moment coursed back into him.

“Is it…?”

The boy nodded. “President Bush, I mean, your father called back to…”

He scrambled across the room and jerked the phone out of the boy’s hands before ushering him to leave. With excitement, he took the call off hold. “Hiya, Poppy!” His voice was shrill and schoolboyish. “Did ya see the results?”

“I flicked through the channels.” There was a long silence. “Almost as impressive as what I did in ‘88.”

The words felt like a knife through his skull. George forced himself to smile. “Yeah, exactly, Poppy…” He walked around the room. In a small monitor, he could see the atrium. He could see the people shouting his name. “I worked real hard for this and not just for me, for Jeb, for the party, for you…”

Static came through the receiver. “What do you want me to say, George? ‘Good job?’”

He stared intensely at the monitor, at the individual pixels. The scene lost coherence. A mass of red and blues. “Yeah, I, I…”

“Well, Christ. ‘Good job.’” The voice was dull, monotonous. George let it bore into him. “Truly, this is a great victory for the family and the party. This will transform Washington and put your name in the history books. Your mother and I are so proud of what you’ve accomplished.” George gripped the receiver hard and listened to his father’s breathing. “Is there anything else you wanted from me? Advice? Finally going to ask me for suggestions on how to handle the next four years?”

George felt himself shaking his head. “N-no, Poppy. Maybe later. Just… um… are you gonna watch my speech?”

There was a long sigh. Suppressed agitation. “It’s late, George. We’ll catch the replay tomorrow. If there’s nothing else, Barbara and I should get to bed. Good night.”

The line went dead. George allowed himself to stand in silence for a few moments in the green room before recomposing his smile. With a cowboy’s confidence, he forced himself to emerge and greet his many smiling aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd in front of him but he could hear their voices.

He stared intensely at the monitor, at the individual pixels. The scene lost coherence. A mass of red and blues. “Yeah, I, I…”

“Well, Christ. ‘Good job.’” The voice was dull, monotonous. George let it bore into him. “Truly, this is a great victory for the family and the party. This will transform Washington and put your name in the history books. Your mother and I are so proud of what you’ve accomplished.” George gripped the receiver hard and listened to his father’s breathing. “Is there anything else you wanted from me? Advice? Finally going to ask me for suggestions on how to handle the next four years?”

George felt himself shaking his head. “N-no, Poppy. Maybe later. Just… um… are you gonna watch my speech?”

There was a long sigh. Suppressed agitation. “It’s late, George. We’ll catch the replay tomorrow. If there’s nothing else, Barbara and I should get to bed. Good night.”

The line went dead. George allowed himself to stand in silence for a few moments in the green room before recomposing his smile. With a cowboy’s confidence, he forced himself to emerge and greet his many smiling aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd in front of him but he could hear their voices.

The excitement inside the Reagan building in downtown DC had been building in the hours before the polls closed. Republicans, decked in red baseball caps and pins and small American flags had descended on the building, excited to see just how badly they beat Robert Byrd. Bush campaign volunteers passed out popcorn while a projection of Fox’s Brit Hume intoned on rock-bottom Democratic turnout and the possibility of a historic outcome. New York could flip, so too could Hawaii. This could be the final, absurd defeat of the Democrat Party and the so-called anti-war movement, he informed the gleeful crowd.

As the hours ticked by, things went along steadily. The president was on track to win victory, and by a margin fit for the christening of what those journalists were calling his “new Republican Party.” Byrd was struggling in the usual blue states, even if a few seemed set to fall into their traditional columns. He was improving on Gore in the Old South, but not by enough to stop the red wave washing over the country. Well before midnight, the networks called it. George W. Bush had won re-election over Robert Byrd. A cheer went up in the crowd.

In his green room, George watched a stream of the assembled people. He bit his lip as he focused on their forced smiles and awkward laughs. He watched a woman wave an enormous sign that read, “BUSH COUNTRY” and displayed the continental United States in crimson red.
But on the TV, the networks were talking about Byrd: what states the old man might actually end up winning, where he had found an appeal, what it might mean. It was like the Republican wins weren’t worth bringing up. George didn’t understand why. He felt like a ghost.

“Sir?”

George turned away from the small television. Standing in the door frame stood his Blake, his bagman. George forced himself to give the boy a smile.

“Heya, Blake,” he said with faux-cheerfulness. In the corner of his eye, he could still see the teeming crowds. “Just getting myself pumped for my, uh, victory speech. What can I do you for?”

“Well, congratulations, sir. I, uh, don’t want to get in the way of your work.” Blake gave the president a smile that showed no teeth. “But you asked me to get you if your father called. The former president, I mean.”

He walked robotically across the room and took the phone out of the boy’s hands before ushering him to leave. After staring at it for a second, he took the call off hold. “Hiya, Poppy!” He tried to make himself sound upbeat. “Did ya see the results?”

“I flicked through the channels.” There was a long silence. “On paper, it’s almost as impressive as what I did in ‘88. It makes me wonder how that might have gone if my opponent back then had one foot in the grave.”

The words felt like a knife through his skull. George forced himself to smile. “Sure, Poppy…” He walked around the room. In a small monitor, he could see the atrium. He could see the people shouting his name. “This could be historic, you know? It’s almost midnight, and Fox still hasn’t called any states for the old bastard yet. I don’t wanna count any chickens before they hatch, but…”

Static came through the receiver. “What do you want me to say, George? ‘Good job?’”

He stared intensely at the monitor, at the individual pixels. The scene lost coherence. A mass of reds and beiges. “Yeah, I, I…”

“Well, Christ. ‘Good job.’” The voice was dull, monotonous. George let it bore into him. “Truly, this is a great victory for the family and the party. Nobody ever thought that you could win by so much against a dementia patient with a Black running mate. Your triumph will ring out for all time.” George gripped the receiver hard and listened to his father’s breathing. “Is there anything else you wanted from me? Advice? Finally going to ask me for suggestions on how to handle the next four years?”

George felt himself shaking his head. He stepped back from the TV and looked at the national map. It was hard to recognize the name on the screen as his own. “N-no, Poppy. Maybe later. Just… um… are you gonna watch my speech?”

There was a long sigh. Suppressed agitation. “It’s late, George. We’ll catch the replay tomorrow. If there’s nothing else, Barbara and I should get to bed. Good night.”

The line went dead. George allowed himself to stand in silence for a few moments in the green room before recomposing his smile. With a cowboy’s confidence, he forced himself to emerge and greet his many smiling aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd in front of him but he could hear their voices.

A Noble Calling

The Ronald Reagan Building in downtown DC shuddered. Within its confines, stood a thousand stamping Republicans. Over the course of the evening, they had watched the election returns with breathless anticipation, not worried by the possibility of defeat but instead excited by the promise of a final, cataclysmic victory over the enemy. They waved their tiny flags as the massive image of Brit Hume was projected overhead.

The crowd trilled as Kentucky and Indiana turned red. They roared as the wave overtook Ohio and Florida. Their bodies shuddered as the red wave flooded into Illinois, New York, and Hawaii. At 2:00 AM, Brit Hume took in a deep breath, and announced that George W. Bush had done the unthinkable. He had won Washington, DC. He had become the first Republican in the history of the country to win all 538 votes. They had called the president insane for his visits to the District and his voter outreach. This was a historic occasion, not one with any parallel in the modern age. Not since Washington had the nation—.

In his green room, George Bush muted his television. He continued to watch as Hume mouthed empty words into the camera, names and faces appearing beneath him. There was a clip of his own rally, the mood bordering on religious ecstasy. There was a picture flashed across the screen of himself, younger, standing next to Jeb and his father. He continued to watch the silent images, which lapsed into an ad for Vicks VapoRub. The tagline promised relief in seconds.

George looked down at his feet and tried to focus intensely on the muffled cheering just outside. By all accounts, he had achieved the stupendous, something impossible. In just two years, he had turned himself from a laughing stock to a kind of icon. He was a uniter. A liberator. A decider. He had vanquished every enemy, foreign and domestic, and achieved everything he had set out to do.

Why, then, did his achievement feel so fleeting? Why did he feel so hollow? He gazed into the television and instead of focusing on the picture, all he could see was his own ghostly reflection in the glass.

There was a knock on the door. George put on his best smile and invited the guest to enter. In walked his bagman, Blake. He continued smiling as the overgrown boy removed a small Blackberry from his pocket.

“Well, first of all, congratulations, sir,” said Blake. George nodded good-naturedly. “Your father just called. I know you wanted to talk with him and…”

“Of course, thank you kindly, Blake. You tell Turd Blossom that I’m gonna talk to Poppy and then I’ll be right out,” He forced a chuckle. “Can’t let these good people wait any longer for this, er, histrionic occasion.”

Blake gave a laugh and then shut the door. George flipped the phone to his ear. “Well, hiya, Poppy. I was wondering when you’d call.” The remark felt pointed and aggressive, but he needed to feel something beyond this dull ache. He needed Poppy to provide him with something to make sense of what was happening. “I trust you gotta be happy with tonight’s outcome?”

“Well, it’s historic. That’s what they keep saying on the television anyways,” Poppy sounded like he was sucking on a piece of sour candy. In his mind’s eye, George could see his father’s tight-lipped expression and the empty glass of bourbon on his desk. “I suppose many consider it impressive.”

“Yeah.”

"Yeah?" His father said.

The void inside him was yawning. The pain was constant. “Yeah, Poppy. It is. I don’t know what more you want me to say.”

““I just want to make sure… it's important that you not let this get to your head... There's an old saying about 'showboating'...'" Poppy drifted off. "It would have been easy to let things go to my head after I won a landslide against Dukakis in ‘88, but I focused on uniting the country… on bringing people together.”

George said nothing. He felt inconsolable.

“This is about uniting the country, not stroking your ego."

The television had returned to broadcasting the pandemonium inside the Ronald Reagan Center. The screen was alight with raining confetti and red and white banners with his name emblazoned on them. He saw a thousand signs with his own smiling face and a bright letter “W” imposed on the wall. George had never felt more desolate in his life. "Sure, Poppy."

"DC didn't used to be this Democratic stronghold, you know" The voice on the other end of the receiver seemed distant. "And this election’s unusual, but there's been plenty of people who won landslides before…"

It had finally become unbearable. "Poppy, I'm afraid I gotta head out. Rove's standing right next to me and pushing me to give my victory speech."

" …who kept in mind the... dignity of the office... the responsibility..."

"Okay, I'll talk to you soon, Poppy.”

"They knew they served beneath the Great Seal and—."

He hung up the phone and was once again alone. He was aware now that there was no hope of transcendence, no possibility of metanoia or spiritual conversion. Standing at the mountaintop and gazing down at the world below, what he felt now was indifference. A void in himself that would never be filled. An entire lifetime of striving to prove himself good enough—for nothing.

He stood a moment longer, then un-hunched his shoulders. With a cowboy’s confidence, he forced himself to emerge from his green room and greet his many smiling aides, slapping them hard on the back or shaking their hands. Then, with Laura at his side, he stepped out onto the stage before blinding stage lights. He could not see the crowd before him but, then again, he no longer cared.

No Higher Honor

FOUR MORE YEARS!” Fox had called the race an hour ago, followed quickly by CNN. He was aware of a hesitant knock on the door of his makeshift green room, but he did not turn. He was too busy luxuriating in the love of the crowd. He closed his eyes and imagined the liberals in Washington weeping and tearing out their hair. He imagined them throwing themselves off buildings.

“Sir?”

“Is it…?”

Washington, D.C., April 28, 2008

The mood was sour as so-called “President” Bush paced outside the Oval Office. While Cheney had never really cared about what Bush did or how he felt, things had become downright flagrant as his “presidency” came to a close. Before, Cheney had at least put in the effort to distract Bush while he ran the country from behind the scenes. Now, he just didn’t care. As he waited to sit behind his favorite desk, all Bush had to focus his small brain on was the voice of Rush from a staffers office.

“You know, Snerdly, we ask a lot on this show what the difference between what this Bush and his pappy is supposed to be. I think the answer’s been staring us in the face the whole time. It’s in the name! The dad was H.W., this one is W. Bush. And you know what that missing H stands for? It’s history! This President will not be remembered by history at all, except as the least consequential ‘leader’ this nation has ever seen. Back then, I marveled at how the media covered Bush 41 as this wimp, no matter how much he gave to them, because he was actually quite strong. He went after Saddam. They said “No war for oil!” and he didn’t blink. But his son wanted those dittoheads to love him, so he did nothing. And they still hate him anyway! It should teach us conservatives a lesson that Ford is learning the hard way: you can’t get very far with a worse version of an old model…”

Just as Bush couldn’t take it anymore, Cheney walked through the door. Swiftly stepping out of the way, Bush spoke, staring at the floor.

“So, heh, hey, Dick. How are things going?”

Cheney turned, looking at him with a scowl. “That’s none of your business.”

Bush chucked like a moron as he lifted his gaze from the ground. “You know, Dick, I was gonna say. Technically, I mean, now that Frist is here, you haven’t been Veep for a few years. So I was thinking that, considering that, that, maybe, heh, you could give me some more time in the Office? At least while I’m on the way out?”

Cheney scowled even harder. “Shut the fuck up.” He spat on him and walked away.

Having braved through the least humiliating thing to happen to him that day, Bush moved towards the Resolute Desk to pretend that he was an actual President. Sitting in his chair, he looked down and saw what Cheney had been working on all day. It was the first draft of his memoirs, titled Monkey See, Monkey Do. Flipping through them at random, he settled on a paragraph in the book’s second chapter.

“—and that was how I got his dumbass bill through Congress. Honestly, I didn’t think it was even a good idea, but I thought, hey, if this moron can’t get anything through, it might start reflecting badly on me, you know? And with a normal president, there’s usually a tit-for-tat here: I help him out, he helps me out. But then when it comes to doing the most basic shit to trade blood for oil [EDITOR’S NOTE: make sure to lie here], he was too much of a coward to do it! God, he’s such a dipshit. Anyways—”

Bush couldn’t bear to read any further. He was devastated. Feeling completely helpless, he prayed to the Lord.

“Oh, God, tell me, why must I suffer so? I have been defiled as Huckabee has rebuked all of my efforts. Condemned by Dick as he has taken credit for my works. Played the fool by Rush as he has condemned me as a footnote. Are the peacemakers not your children? Somebody tag in God. God, if you can hear me, God, please save me. Please save me, God, please. I’m asking you.”

Suddenly, he felt a presence and heard a voice from the Heavens. “Do not be afraid, my child. I have been watching. Know that all that has happened over these eight years was by my design. You should fear not, as all that has occurred is exactly what you wanted.”

Shrieking, Bush jumped and hid behind “his” desk. Trembling, he asked, “Oh, Lord, how can this be? How can this be what I wanted? In spite of my trials, I have nothing.”

For a moment, God was silent. Then, he spoke. “Oops. Wrong George Bush. Uhhh. Darn. My bad.” The presence left as quickly as it came.

Still trembling, Bush slowly stood up, looking outside the window of the Oval Office. It was snowing that April. The lawn was immaculately trimmed, the hard work of people who had actually held a real job once in their lives. Staring at the falling snow much as an infant would at a set of jangling keys, he moved his gaze towards the hedges just outside the window. Hidden beneath the white blankets of snow, the White House greenery appeared smaller than usual. What once looked like a mighty bush now seemed to be nothing more than a lowly shrub.

The plant looked back at the “President.” It had no eyes, but it saw itself.

Poppy

Misfire
by Bob Woodward
Simon & Schuster, 390 pp., $22.95
Shadow War: The Hidden History of Afghanistan from the Soviets to the Americans
by Sam Gold
Penguin Press, 710 pp., $39.95

SEPTEMBER 19, 2007 ISSUE

On the cusp of the American invasion’s fourth anniversary next month, I found myself chatting with a well-off contractor in his newly constructed villa. If you looked around the capital city—which had been so eviscerated by clashing factions in the 1990’s—you would be forgiven for wondering if there was even a war going on. But my wealthy host told me such fantasies don’t outlast their first brush with the countryside. “Go east, and you’ll be mugged by reality,” he said with a grin.

Those in another capital city we call Washington seem to forget we are currently at war in Afghanistan too, judging by the conflicting answers one gets when they pose a simple question to any official in government: just how many Americans are fighting in Afghanistan? “Fuck if I know,” one veteran State Department analyst sighed. Officially, the Pentagon discloses that 24,000 American troops are in the country, and that’s not counting the number of contractors, which is at least double. Most troops are stationed in Kabul and a handful of other provincial capitals.

The brunt of the fighting is done by proxy forces—scattered militias recruited for petty cash, the much-lambasted Afghan National Police Force, and opium smugglers. It’s a fact which the CIA is finding harder to deny, considering the news elsewhere in the region.

The latter is something most Americans only hear about in the context of the ongoing Iraqi insurgency—or liberation/terrorist movement, depending on who you ask. Salafist militant groups have festered since the late 1990s in the country, when mujahideen veterans (known as the “Arab Afghans” by the CIA veterans of that earlier dirty war) returned to their homes across the Mid-East, coinciding with a weakening of the Iraqi government via sanctions, bombings, and more. With many of al-Qaeda’s top leaders eluding capture in Afghanistan, plenty have turned up in propaganda videos produced by violent groups in Iraq. Their rank-and-file have been kept alive via a lifeline of poppy production back in Afghanistan, raising enough money for arms on the black market.

Today, most American news is filled with images of bombed out buses and Shia Muslims fleeing their family homes for fear of reprisal, all while an increasingly feeble Saddam Hussein vows “annihilation” for those who oppose him. UN debates over whether acts of any side of this bloody conflict constitute intent to destroy particular protected groups will drag on for many months. But if you scour the dark corners of the internet, the origins of this war are already solved. Plenty of conspiracy blogs feed their paranoid readers visions of darkened C-130s dropping weapons to the Jihadist groups like Jama'at, all while pointing to the fabled Operation Cyclone of the 1980s as precedent for American intelligence agencies arming radical Islamist groups.

Their fuzzy view of history notwithstanding, foreign intervention in the Iraqi bloodshed is the worst kept secret of the war. Those planes full of weapons for fighters eager to oust Saddam may not have come directly from the Americans, but they certainly were sent by our close Gulf allies. As for the surge in alarming sectarian hatred across the region, one has to ask our friends in the House of Saud about their recent record media buy to put hatemongers on the air in the Middle East’s biggest television networks. Those madrassas don’t build themselves.

But it would be all too easy to simply shrug the chaos off as an incurable disease afflicting the region, beset by religious extremism. We have plenty of that at home in spades. If you want to witness what our own hatemongers look like on TV, don’t forget just how eager many of our finest commentators were to tout the most absurd fabrications about Saddam Hussein just a few short years ago. Now, as Bob Woodward shows in his latest expose of the Bush White House, most of these sources came straight from the top.

Despite the tumult in the administration over their ultimate failure to go to war, there’s zero indication it’s fallen from the president’s agenda. Three separate White House sources have told me that President Bush is a “fanatic” about Saddam. “There’s nobody else on the planet who makes the president as nuts as that asshole does,” remarked one administration official. Beyond the rants and ravings from the president about how “this guy tried to kill my dad,” that Woodward’s earlier book made headlines for, there’s still a real ideological fervor for any plan that would remove Saddam Hussein from power.

Even with all the firings in the wake of the debacle over whether to vote for an invasion of Iraq, all roads lead back to the same group of neoconservatives who had such great influence over the president in his first few years in office. “They never really left,” a senior source tells Woodward. “You see them bitching on the Sunday shows now and then, whether it’s about North Korea or whatever, but the president talks with them all on a practically daily basis.”

One hardly needs to be a Straussian to read between the lines on the latest headlines about the Iraqi crisis. The largest U.S. military aid package to Saudi Arabia in history was confirmed earlier this year, despite serious questions from Congress over allegations that they protected senior al-Qaeda leaders who escaped from Afghanistan. The next month, The Washington Post reports that a Saudi prince promised leaders of the Iraqi insurgents billions worth of arms in a Riyadh meeting. Now, still limping from his last attempt, President Bush is sounding the alarm on Saddam again. “Some folks like to stop before the job is done,” he told the White House press pool, grimacing, “but that’s not the way we do business here.” That trademark Texas charm was gone. All that was left was barely concealed rage.

As Woodward reports, after the press conference, Bush muttered to him, “we’re gonna do it goddamn right this time.”

Let’s Go Places in Syria
By Nathan Hide Published December 2, 2008 | Comments (970)

Amidst the turmoil wracking the housing market, the auto industry is near collapse, and the U.S. Federal Reserve shows no will to keep credit moving. Republican allies of President Bush are already urging him to “let Detroit go bankrupt,” and General Motors is in terminal crisis. The biggest—perhaps the only—beneficiary? Daesh.

Experts agree that in a warzone like Syria dominated by radical groups and with no central authority, the black market is bound to thrive. Toyota vehemently denounces the use of their Land Cruisers by ISIL.

Officials in Washington are growing alarmed by the ubiquity of the truck however, and top Toyota executives will appear before Congress next week to explain the issue. Toyota maintains it’s their policy “not to sell vehicles to customers who may use or modify them for illicit activities, including terrorism.” But experts agree there is simply no way to accurately track how many trucks have been stolen or sold through the black market to groups like Daesh or al-Nusra in Syria.

Toyota tells Jalopnik that the vehicles seen in videos being commandeered by terrorists in Syria are not recent models. “These are very outdated models,” one executive said, “we don’t use them anymore.” Legal sales of trucks in Iraq in 2007 were quadruple the number sold in 2006, according to a report from the U.S. State Department. That total in 2008 is expected several times higher, due to the sinking auto market here in the United States.

For some Ford executives, it’s an unfortunate inevitability of the wars abroad and the economic crisis at home. “I just wish they were driving F-150s,” one lamented.

WASHINGTON (NBC) -- For the first time in over two years, over 40 percent of Americans approve of President Bush, largely in response to low gas prices and success in foreign affairs.

CLASSIFIED/21 July 2007

OFFICE OF THE VICE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES

Dear Kate, Elizabeth, Grace, Philip, Richard and Sam,

I write this message to you at a time of great international uncertainty. As Vice President, my principal focus has been to protect the American people and our way of life. Though I’ve faced many challenges in this time, none represent those posed by the lawless regime overseen by Vladimir Putin, who has rejected every hand of friendship in favor of violence. Even now, his allies have embarked on a senseless campaign of shelling the Republic of Georgia. Our intelligence leaders—who have been unwaveringly diligent and committed to preserving the democratic zone of peace—indicate he intends to expand these operations in an attempt to restore the old Russian empire.

While I never sought the immense responsibility placed on me at this precise moment, as our president faces a serious medical procedure and is rendered unable to serve as commander-in-chief, I cannot shirk my duties either. I have a special obligation to the brave members of our armed forces, intelligence community, law enforcement agencies, and others who serve and sacrifice to keep us free. My oath of office calls me to support and defend the Constitution of the United States, even if that means taking tough decisions that others may criticize. I accept this criticism as part of our free and fair process.

Tomorrow, you will wake up in a new world. While my advisors reassure me that our national defenses are strong and more than capable of preventing attacks from reaching American soil, all defenses are imperfect and there may be some costs to the actions which I am about to undertake. I want you all to know that I carefully considered the options available and elected to take a path that inflicted the least harm, that would minimize the loss of life for our patriotic men and women and permanently eradicate a threat to a free and democratic world order.

As you grow, you will come to understand the sacrifices that each generation makes to preserve freedom and democracy for future generations. One day, you will assume the important responsibilities of citizens in our society. God willing, you will not face the same kinds of choices that I do now. Whatever the future holds, I ask of you as my grandchildren what I asked of my daughters, that you always strive in your lives to do what is right.


May God bless and protect you.

Richard B. Cheney
Acting President of the United States
(Grandpa Cheney)

Jihadi Johnny 2008? The surprising connection between ISIL propaganda and American campaign ads

motherjones.com
Heather Richards | Aug. 28 2007

A grainy black-and-white photo of President Wellstone at a funeral service for American soldiers killed in Iraq. Charts and statistics flashing by purporting to depict skyrocketing suicide rates among veterans. A voiceover promising the viewers that there’s a better way, that this grim reality isn’t all there is, that they can change things.

Does this description best fit ISIL’s terrifying propaganda videos proliferating over every dark corner of the internet? Or Mike Huckabee’s latest campaign ad sent out over Iowa networks this week?

Why not both?

ISIL’s propaganda mill has alarmed experts in both videography and mapping religious extremists. Their videos rack up millions of views, and are often shown on mainstream American cable news channels like FOX or CNN. Wellstone even had to address them at a press conference last month, stressing he was “strongly concerned” by the uptick in American recruits for the terrorist group, but urging that “these maniacs prey on fear, and we can’t play into that.”

The group uses sophisticated animation techniques in their videos, and has increasingly targeted U.S. political figures across both parties—Wellstone, George Bush, and John McCain are frequently shown. It’s hard not to notice the similarities to our own political propaganda during election season. A candidate will air attack ads against their opponent, painting them as out-of-touch, corrupt, or even blasphemous.

“It goes even further than just the video techniques,” said Erin Hart, an expert on religious extremist movements at Harvard. “ISIL’s whole appeal is to young frustrated men in the west, often from well-educated middle class families, who feel that the world has slighted them. ISIL preys on this by catering to their misogyny certainly, but also feelings of abandonment in an increasingly globalized world.”

In a widely circulated open letter signed by hundreds of Imams and Islamic scholars this February, ISIL’s total rejection of centuries of scholarship was stressed. But again, Hart explains, that’s something the group plays into. “They’re very anti-establishment in that way, tilting themselves against vast fields of study, which they just toss into the wood-chipper. They’re intensely individualistic.”

Promises of a better world beyond our own way of life, preying on masculine insecurities, and posting graphic online videos to terrify minorities? It sounds a lot more like a Rick Perry rally than the Arab conquests.

Tucker Carlson | @tuckercarlsonmsnbc
April 13, 2007 at 10:49 AM

“His brain has not only been washed, as they say, it has been dry cleaned.” If you’ve ever watched the Angela Lansbury/Frank Sinatra classic The Manchurian Candidate, then the idea of a president secretly beholden to a foreign power is nothing new. It’s a common trope in fiction, and even some conspiracy theories. But I’m not talking about strange web forums or old movies. No, this is far more important. No matter what the liberal media thinks, we’ve reached a point where it is only fair to ask: is President Al Sharpton a Russian Manchurian Candidate?

It’s not a far-fetched question. When running for office, Sharpton excoriated President Bush’s freedom agenda, attacking our troops in Afghanistan and Iraq, while alleging there was some mysterious group of “neocons” behind it all—whatever that even means. But after his stunning upset victory, I was willing to give Sharpton a shot. After all, revitalizing the economy at home and bringing the troops back from poorly executed foreign adventures couldn’t be all bad.

In office, however, Sharpton sounded a different tune. The president tried to slash vital CIA programs that provided a lifeline for the brave resistance fighters in Syria, battling a murderous dictatorship strongly supported by the Russians and Iranians. When old Soviet MIGs picked off the CIA’s top fighters like ants, Sharpton told Keith Olberman that these brave warriors were “linked to terrorists.” Putting the anti-Muslim rhetoric aside, it’s a line straight out of Russian propaganda, and I bet it made Vladimir Putin grin.

The Republican Savior is in the House
Are Syria's Chemical Weapons Iraq's Missing WMD? Start Asking the Real Questions
Peace in Iran’s Time

An end to all airstrikes and cutting off support for anti-regime fighters, in exchange for…what exactly? Some inscrutable gas pipeline arrangements in Eastern Europe and a removal of chemical weapons from Syria?

Now, all reasonable Americans can agree that it’s prudent for the commander-in-chief to think carefully before intervening around the world, and that a primary goal of any sensible foreign policy should be bringing our troops back home. But we can’t ignore how Sharpton set about doing this. Criticize the invasion of Iraq all you want, but Bush learned his lesson in Syria. As Commander-in-Chief, Bush authorized only limited aerial bombardment and stuck to backing proxies on the ground who were ready and willing to take the fight to a Russian puppet. What exactly is the problem with that?

Let's dispel once and for all with this fiction that Al Sharpton doesn't know what he's doing. He knows exactly what he's doing. Sharpton is Putin’s man in the White House.

As for that shock election upset in 2004, Republicans in Congress need to be asking some serious questions. Few dare to ask the question, but let’s just lay it right out: did Vladimir Putin steal the 2004 election?

Open letter to President Sharpton

MacroWest Solutions
macrowest.com
January 28, 2007
Open letter to President Sharpton

Dear President Sharpton,

We are writing because we are concerned by the growing instability in the Indo-Pacific, and that if action is not immediately taken, our nation may soon face a threat in East Asia greater than any since the end of the Cold War. In your West Point speech on Iraq last month, the path you laid out toward a nuclear free Korean Peninsula was well-articulated, and we applaud the steps you have taken towards a withdrawal deadline in Afghanistan and Iraq. Yet we are increasingly convinced that your administration should allocate those resources to Asia, rather than looking further inward.

The challenges at home require your close attention, but the best pathway to a prosperous middle class is through expanding our defense industrial base to meet the challenge in the Pacific. With this new Congress still negotiating your budget, we believe it would be prudent to increase expenditures for the U.S. Navy and Air Force, while trimming back spending on the Green Berets and other unnecessary special operations forces. With the hot wars in the Middle East and Central Asia winding down, these expenses become not only overbearing but detrimental to national security.

As you know, our Navy continues to shrink, with poorly planned post-Cold War cuts to our defense budget gutting the numbers of cruisers, destroyers, and even aircraft carriers. This is unconscionable in the face of the growing crises in the Indo-Pacific. To face future contingencies and ensure the United States remains dominant in great power competition, production of these forces must be accelerated. Furthermore, pitching these policy changes to a war-weary public will require emphasizing their domestic benefits. This will bring manufacturing back home, after years of offshoring jobs to our enemies. You can even say the Washington playbook has failed. After all, in the wake of a resurgent enemy in the East, it’s hard to argue that the previous administrations have taken this threat seriously.

We are living in a moment that will determine the fate of the world for generations to come. We must be able to look our children and grandchildren in the eye and tell them that we ensured that American dominance will last beyond their lifetimes. We urge you to take decisive action. Leave every option on the table. This is a battle between the enlightened free world and backwater authoritarian enemies hellbent on imposing their vision across the planet. This is a war between the children of light and the children of darkness. To do anything less would be to ensure that the 21st century will be a Chinese Century.

Sincerely,

Read more: Joe Lieberman, John McCain

Forward! or Retreat?

Forward! Party strategist Mark Penn released a memo last week suggesting that the increasingly polarized nature of American politics had opened up a “middle lane” in the 2008 presidential contest, one that Forward! and its nominee President Lieberman would be able to exploit.

His findings—one supported by focus group discussions from messaging guru Frank Luntz—emphasize something that has become all-too-common knowledge for Beltway experts: That the two parties have become captured by their base and have drifted too far from the center of the country.

A series of nasty primary challenges against the advocates of the 2005 Iraq AUMF has led long-established party hands to be replaced with partisans unwilling to reach across the aisle. Life in Washington has become, to borrow from Hobbes, nasty, brutish, and short.

The only question now is how many partisans leave the safe harbors offered by the two parties for the unruly waters offered by Forward!

While Lieberman, Cheney, Cowan, and Penn have been vocal in extolling the virtues of their new party—at time brushing up against the Hatch Act—polling from Pew shows that Americans have remained hesitant to leap aboard, with only 13 percent of Americans reporting a “great level of interest” in changing political affiliation.

But, as Penn insists in his memo, the reason for this number has less to do with Americans’ lack of support for the president, his wars, or his middle-of-the-road policies and more with what its advocates acknowledge as a “rocky start.”

After facing a competitive primary challenge from John Edwards and subsequently leaving the party, Lieberman and his allies first attempted to take over the long-irrelevant Reform Party. An embarrassing fight with the Reform Party’s founders led Lieberman and his Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney (effectively number-two after Mary Landrieu’s exile to the Naval Observatory), to launch the Independence Party, later restyled Forward! An attempted launch of a “web platform” to allow small-dollar party donors to propose and vote on the party’s platform was canceled after several embarrassing planks gained traction.

Despite these problems, the centrist faction, self-consciously modeled off the Liberal Democrats in the United Kingdom, has recruited a spattering of state officials and sixteen House Democrats and two House Republicans—most of whom faced uphill primaries against challengers criticizing their support of Lieberman’s invasion of Iraq and his “limited strikes and engagements” in Libya, Somalia, and Mali.

Lieberman and Cheney have proven unable to get any Senators to join his cause, but rumors have circulated in recent weeks that the president and his allies have embarked on a campaign to sway Lieberman’s long-time friend John McCain. An anonymous source informed the Washington Post that Lieberman had pitched McCain on being his running mate in 2008, with a promise to give the maverick “free rein” on the Iran issue if successful.

I’ll keep you informed as this story develops. Whether Lieberman’s Forward! turns out to be his Asterlitz or Waterloo remains to be seen.

23 Nov. 2005

President Wellstone’s White House is brimming with ideological zealots. No, not the old New Lefties turned liberals trying to push an expansive healthcare bill through an unwilling Congress. Not the protectionist warriors picking up the sword of Ross Perot to cut free trade agreements to ribbons. MUDDYING THE WATERS

Red Lines
newyorker.com/magazine
Annals of National Security May 5, 2007 Issue
By Seymour M. Hersh
April 23, 2007

MUDDYING THE WATERS

Since taking office, after his predecessor’s last few potshots at Bashar al-Assad’s regime in Syria, President Wellstone’s strategy in the third American war in so many years has confounded experts. The White House immediately ceased all U.S. airstrikes in Syria, while still pledging to “keep the option on the table,” without specifying what action would trigger further intervention. Meanwhile, the chaos since October 2004 has consumed the country, spiraling into a destructive civil war and destabilizing the greater region. President Wellstone and his advisors tell the press they remain committed to seeing Assad leave power, but are mum on how they plan to get there.

Further complicating matters, Russian President Vladimir Putin has vowed to strengthen one of the last old Soviet client regimes in the Middle East, but likewise has refused to specify how he plans to do it. The European press is filled with sightings of Spetsnaz special forces spotted in the suburbs of Damascus and freighters filled with old Soviet weapons bound for Syria halted before they leave Croatia.

More from The New Yorker:
“We Know that They Know that We Know:” Adam Curtis’ new feature on healthcare, the Middle East, and the dot com bubble
The Cell that Struck London | Steve Coll

When pressed on the matter, President Putin has demurred, suggesting that any overt U.S. military role in Syria would trigger a sharp Russian reaction. President Wellstone has also refused to set a firm red line, with his answer changing practically week-to-week. At his infamous press conference in May 2005, Wellstone mentioned “seeing a lot of chemical weapons” as a condition in which he would launch a deeper intervention. The White House quickly walked that comment back, but National Security Advisor James Steinberg said the next month that the administration’s red line was the fall of rebel-held Aleppo (this past week marked the second year of the Syrian government’s siege on the northern city).

Finally, Wellstone appears to have settled on a rough red line. According to three senior administration officials, the president will fully commit the U.S. to a full-scale military intervention in Syria if the Russians intervene first. “The hope is that it’s a MAD thing,” one top State Department appointee told me. “Like if they’re not going in if we don’t go in, then we won’t go in if they don’t go in.”

Such tenuous agreements appear to be holding for now, yet what goes unremarked upon often in Washington is that both the U.S. and Russia have already fully committed to a “military solution” in Syria. It’s covert only to the public, but in the halls of power, these decisions are well-known. As has been referenced in the mainstream papers on occasion, the CIA has been carrying out a large covert action program to arm the rebels, in liaison with Saudi intelligence, to the tune of at least $1 billion per year. The FSB too has spent a fortune funneling surplus Soviet stock weapons to Assad and his allies in Hezbollah, with one classified Pentagon analysis calculating its cost at over $2 billion since 2005 alone.

THE CROATIAN CONNECTION

In a report from The New York Times last December, the source of the CIA’s guns for the Syrian rebels was revealed: a port in the Croatian city of Dubrovnik. Assets on the ground move the weapons (including advanced BGM-1 TOW missiles) on to large freighters owned by CIA cutouts, which then set sail for Lebanon, where they’re smuggled over the border with Syria.

Where do the Russians send their weapons from? The same Dubrovnik port.

“It’s Looney Toons shit,” one agency veteran with ongoing contacts inside the CIA remarked. “I mean the Cold War days were pretty nuts, but this is something else.” Two sources told me they’ve heard unconfirmed reports that some of the CIA’s guns for the rebels and FSB’s guns for pro-regime forces even traveled on the same ships.

When I asked administration officials whether the U.S. covertly backing one side in a civil war against an opposing side supported by Russia amounted to a proxy war, they laughed it off. “I mean sure, if that’s what you want to call it,” a White House source remarked.

The CIA itself is reportedly deeply frustrated by the whole affair, even as President Wellstone still wavers on when and how he will send the US military into Syria. A top Middle Eastern intelligence expert aware of the operations chuckled, “it’s all politics.” Many inside the CIA are equally cynical. “If he wants to have a working relationship with Putin and not put his nuts in a twist with all the NATO bullshit on Georgia and Ukraine, fine. And if he wants to get involved in the civil war directly, alright. But Christ, does he have to do both at the same time?” ♦

Published in the print edition of the May 5, 2007, issue.

By Lou Dobbs
CNN

Thursday, February 3, 2008

WASHINGTON (CNN) — Amid a slowing economy and a parade of congressional investigations, President John Edwards used his State of the Union address Monday night to champion recent bipartisan foreign policy initiatives spearheaded by the White House.

For informed political observers, the Address offered little new. Edwards did not address the personal and professional scandals that have plagued his administration nor did he reveal any new approach to the health care reform bill currently trapped in committee. Prior to the address, senior aides had sought to downplay expectations. Instead, Edwards celebrated what he described as the “New Consensus for a New Century,” a collection of policies meant to advance and preserve America’s place in a rapidly changing world.

“What the New Consensus offers is not hard power, not soft power, but smart power. With evidence-based and mission-driven policies, crafted by our nation’s foremost experts, the world once again feels the full weight of America’s moral leadership.”

With specific call-outs that at times made him resemble an award show host more than an officer of the United States, Edwards highlighted contributions to the “New Consensus” from Senators Richard Lugar (R-IN), John McCain (R-AZ) Joe Biden (D-DE), and Hillary Clinton (D-NY).

These successes included Edwards’s signature “Marshall Corps” of peacebuilding experts to help failing states, funded by private-sector contributions and cuts to his predecessor’s “wasteful and bloated” PEPFAR program. They also included the 4 billion-dollar military operation “Good Intention” to train the militaries of Central Africa and assist in the capture of Joseph Kony of the Lord's Resistance Army.

Edwards celebrated the successes of the group “Invisible Children” whose leaders Jason Russell and Laren Poole attended as guests and the “passion of American youth to serve as leaders for the world.”

“My Administration will continue to look to new voices, soliciting input from our new public square—the World Wide Web. Sites like www.kony2008.com play a critical role in setting the tone of our new national discourse.”

DeathCabKitty’s LiveJournal: The Birth of a Meme, or Why I Love the Internet (Part One Billion)

Previous Entry | Next Entry
November 1, 2008 at 1:14 PM

It’s November, which means we’re in the middle of that age-old tradition where the American people go through the motions of choosing a candidate of someone else’s choosing. In the age of the internet, this solemn tradition has been augmented with flame wars, epithets, and trolling. There’s been high moments (still rofling at whoever wore their fursuit to meet Tipper Gore) and low (just take a look at some of the cringey Republican outreach on TheFacebook).

Today, I want to focus on one of the highest highs, a moment that shows the kinds of creativity and community that’s possible on the World Wide Web. I want to talk about the #thompsondeathrally.

If you missed it, #thompsondeathrally was a meme on Twitter, a web blog site that launched about two years ago where you can only post up to 140 characters. When it launched, most of the users were people in tech and there were only sporadic posts, but membership has surged over the election to 1.5+ million users and almost 5 million messages a day. It’s crazy growth in the middle of a recession and one of the things that contributed to this rise was #thompsondeathrally.

If you do a search on Twitter for #thompsondeathrally, you’ll find some of the best group fiction ever. The posts tell a strange, disjointed account of a political rally straight out of H.P. Lovecraft, with bizarre rites taking place on stage to rescue Fred Thompson’s flailing campaign.

GreenDamien @thegreenster
Fred Thompson opens with a shoutout to his “Fred Heads.” He then reveals what appears to be the severed head of Ronald Reagan. It begins to scream. #ThompsonDeathRally
David Daniels @ddaniels213
“No child left behind!” Campaign volunteers separate a mother from her children. They’re dragging them to the stage. I see the glint of a knife. #ThompsonDeathRally
Aubrey Lee @swordnstoner
Thompson-Frist, Frist-Thompson. Nominee and running mate merge as one. This is the only way to assure party unity, they say with two mouths.
#ThompsonDeathRally
adam t @athomthompson
“Life begins at implantation.” The masses shriek with delight as Thompson vomits another glistening egg into a woman’s open mouth. #ThompsonDeathRally
The hash tag went on for days as the Internet hive-mind put together a communal vision of a nightmarish rally.
Obama 2012 @georgeyjordans3
“We will re-privatize health care. We will re-privatize sanity. We will re-privatize God.” #ThompsonDeathRally
Candy Morgennthau @camorgenn
Bush flails as they lay him out on the altar. His father is brought out after him. No more tolerance for failure. #ThompsonDeathRally
Problem Sleuth @mspafan
#thompsondeathrally staffers keep saying we need to stop the troop withdrawal, finish the job. It’s a chant. The moon turns blood-red.
Suzanne Wallace @suzieqwallacee
A sting on my arm. When I look down, a locust with Oliver North’s face is gorging messily on my flesh. I understand now. #thompsondeathrally
Even I got in on the action.
Laurie Childs @deathcabbkitty
Mike Huckabee stands inside an effigy made to resemble the Green Cities Act. With a wide smile, he lights a match. #ThompsonDeathRally
Eventually some reporters took notice. The Chicago Tribune published a bemused article titled, “Internet Geeks Imagine Thompson Using ‘Satanic Powers’ (describing Lovecraft as Satanic makes me wince but we). The weirdos at Breitbart, meanwhile, published something with the title, “Twitter Users Threaten Thompson, Republicans.” Losers.

Like a lot of memes, this whole thing started small, not as a set of “death threats” against Fred Thompson (as much as I’m sure he would love the attention. According to data nerd Nate Silver, he’s polling in the mid-40s in must-win states). It started because he held a campaign rally in Pennsylvania. Then it started to get cold and, for whatever reason, his security refused to let people leave. After the fact, they told people it was because of “security” (though I think we all know it’s because he didn’t want the cameras seeing him talking to no one).

The whole thing is a PR own-goal from Thompson, sparked by staffers doing something really stupid and reporters being bored by a dull election. As much as I’m sure Thompson and Hilldawg would love Gore to lose (did you see her complaining about Gore going “far left” ever since he grew that beard lawl), I don’t think it’s going to happen unless they really do summon Cthulhu.

Anyways, I’d encourage you to register a Twitter account and see the rest of the posts yourself. I’ll return to my usual Harry Potter posting once this election is over. Until then, enjoy!

Eagle Forum Newsletter | August 25, 2008

Our economic problems are not just because of the China issue.
