“Unfit to Print”

http://www.andrewsullivan.com/

The Daily Dish
Email Article | Print Version | Black & White

Saturday, June 2, 2007

The theater critics will disagree, but the address on the aircraft carrier was an effective campaign address. The president is exactly right to remind the people of America that we won the war; that we’ve liberated a people with minimal casualties (the incident at the Italian consulate notwithstanding); that we are right to remain ever vigilant in an ever-more insecure age. I deeply admire Hillary for going out there and taking responsibility for the entire thing. Listening to her talk about building the “pillars of democracy” to liberate “an entire generation of women” gave me goosebumps.

But I do think Jonathan Alter in The Atlantic has a point that the whole set-up, the backdrop, the sign gives off a certain—how do I say this?—neediness. It’s one thing to give a speech commemorating the liberation of a country and another thing entirely to do so on America’s biggest aircraft carrier, off the coast of Tripoli, surrounded by flags and cheering men in uniform. Our soldiers deserve to be seen and recognized, but I fear critics will read the entire ceremony as revealing of a deep insecurity. Like the president needs to convince America they did the right thing—and that’s not right.

And anyone notice how little WMDs came up in the speech? What’s up with that?

12.48 AM

Wednesday, June 6, 2007

After the invasion of Libya, there was chaos. These things are unavoidable in wars. Even The Aeneid, there’s descriptions of anarchy that will be all too familiar to the late-night television viewer. Consider:

The ancient city fell that had for many years
Been queen. Corpses lay piled everywhere,
In the streets, the houses, the hallowed thresholds
Of the temples. And it was not only the Trojans
Who paid in blood.

In the aftermath of President Clinton’s speech, I’ve been going back and forth over Stanley Lombardo’s new translation of The Aeneid to steel myself. As CNN broadcasts new videos of the air strikes on Benghazi—far more devastating than anyone thought—I have to remind myself that these things have always happened.

I know that Clinton and Clark are juggling a lot of competing interests and they have to put a bright face forward, but I think even the excuses start to wear thin at a certain point. If our armed forces took every effort to minimize casualties, then why did the Administration fight tooth and nail to delay release of these videos until after Qhaddafi had been hung and the president had done her speech? It doesn’t make sense. It feels like a throwback to a more primitive era than the Trojan War..

No matter how unavoidable it is, chaos is still chaos. Death is still death. The United States still has a responsibility to the people of Libya—hence the “Responsibility to Protect.” If the goal here is to restore “order” and to “keep the peace,” then this kind of behavior sends the wrong message. What are our partners in the future Libyan government supposed to learn from the greatest democracy on earth relying on these kinds of tactics? How are we supposed to face our friends in Italy, who are burying their dead after a US missile hit their consulate compound? Surely, we are better than this.

3.48 AM

Thursday, June 7, 2007

New New York Times poll today. A month into the intervention—it’s hard not to notice how the Clinton White House insists this is an “intervention” not an “invasion”—a majority of Americans still approve of the job the president is doing (54-34). Dicier situation on the whole Libya issue, with only 51 percent approving a month out and 47 disapproving. President only doing slightly better on “other foreign policy issues” with 53 approving of her job overall.

Maybe the situation will change once more people hear the aircraft carrier speech. I don’t know. The president has always had a likability issue, not that it’s fair.

Beyond the warning signs coming from Wall Street (which Hillary has no control over, Republican complaints about Fannie Mae and Secretary Johnson’s ties to them notwithstanding), the biggest issue is the WMDs situation. Namely: Where are they? Were they destroyed? Smuggled out? Sold? Is it possible that the program was far less along than we thought but, if that’s the case, what about the mobile chemical weapons units that Clark testified to Congress about? What about the sarin gas sample that Ambassador Albright presented to the United Nations? We need to know exactly what happened here, whether the president was deceived or the intelligence services were wildly incompetent. I don’t know the answer; but I do know we need one.

If we made a mistake, it’s better just to cop to that and move on. Personally, I always supported the war on humanitarian grounds. It was always outrageous what Qhaddafi was doing to his people and I think most Americans will accept the “responsibility to protect” argument. We just need a definitive explanation for this and other failures so they don’t happen again and it doesn’t seem like the president “tricked” the American people. We need something so the usual types—Gravel, Maher, Moore—don’t succeed in their effort to turn Clinton into a new Nixon.

1.52 PM

Tuesday, June 12, 2007

A new report from Julian Borger of The Guardian today on the British perspective of the increasingly embarrassing absence of chemical and biological weapons in Libya and Blair’s attempts to pivot to a “humanitarian” angle:

An intensive six-month search of Libya for weapons of mass destruction has failed to come up with anything to support the stories used by the Blair Administration to go to war, says a new report by a joint CIA-MI6 task force.

The interim report, which remains highly classified, describes only an “intention and capacity” to build banned weapons. Its leak has already caused reverberations through the British political establishment and there is now a debate over whether the government will risk releasing it at all.

“It’s a terrible thing,” said one government source. “I expect they’ll try to sell it as a preemptive measure and a humanitarian thing, but it demonstrates that one of the main judgments in the march to war, that Qaddafi had hundreds of tons of chemical and biological weapons ready, are false.”

Downing Street last night officially dismissed the leak as speculation, A No 10 spokesman said: “People should wait. The reports today are speculation from an unfinished draft that has not been presented or approved.”

A BBC report yesterday described how Blair had spoken to disgruntled members of his party about Qaddafi’s long history of flouting international law and his extensive list of human rights abuses. The Prime Minister urged MPs not to “overreact” to developing events and instead focus on “long-term goals and priorities.”


Overmuch, me thinks. Blair had best hope that there’s nothing to Hersh’s reports of “suppressed” stories of popular unrest in Libya. Otherwise, he might experience something like accountability.

1.52 PM

Friday, June 15, 2007

After today’s riots, I think it’s pretty clear the Pentagon seriously misjudged the post-war situation in Libya. More dead. State and USAID personnel wounded. I think the president is supposed to deliver remarks tonight with good news: more troops and more attention to pacify the country and support the new transitional government, but it isn’t good. Rumor also on the street that the Europeans are planning a response to the Italian consulate issue—a coordinated reduction in US diplomatic staff across the continent.

It’s not good. It’s really not good. War plans are designed to be flexible and they need to be to achieve any kind of success. Let’s hope Clark still has some strength in him before this entire situation slips out of our control. We can’t afford a delay in the nation-building process, lest we betray the young women that President Clinton so eloquently defended earlier this month.

11.55 PM

Thursday, June 21, 2007

Looks like Clark’s out at Defense. Petraeus is in. All signs point to a serious screw-up in Libya, with the Pentagon struggling to handle the growing presence of extremist groups from regions as far-flung as Afghanistan (try to spell “al-Qaeda” without looking it up, I dare you). New York Times has a devastating account from one one-time pro-war writer on the collapse of services in Tripoli and US forces reduced to the city’s heavily fortified center.

If voters won’t punish Clinton for finding no WMDs, maybe they’ll punish her for letting Libya collapse into civil war. If rumor is to be believed, Cheney’s gearing up to launch soon with a promise to “clean up” the mess left behind by his two predecessors.

If it’s true, at least we’ll finally have some competence in government for a change.

FiveThirtyEight Blog: On the Road: Des Moines, Iowa

Posted by Sean Quinn at 4:44 PM, October 14

There were the most beautiful bevies of girls everywhere I looked in Des Moines that afternoon — they were coming home from high school — but I had no time now for thoughts like that and promised myself a ball in Denver… . So I rushed past the pretty girls, and the prettiest girls in the world live in Des Moines.

—John Kerouac, The Road


Most of her life, Janice Reynolds lived life as a Republican, volunteering for Bush in 1992 and his son in 2000. After Hillary tossed her hat in the ring in 2004 and she saw an opportunity to elect America’s first female president, Janice threw herself into life as a “Hillary for America” organizer. She had high hopes for the re-election campaign in 2008, but she had questions, namely: “Why aren’t we canvassing yet?”

Accustomed to the energy of the ‘04 race, it seemed strange to her that Hillary’s campaign was letting go of the network of activist women that had brought it so much success a few years ago. People aren’t knocking on doors or organizing any more “women’s potlucks” in Des Moines. Phonebanking, sure, but it seemed like in the final stretch the campaign is being asked to pursue different tactics to halt Dolementum.

“They have all these data consultants who tell us where to direct our energy,” says Janice, settling into her role as one of Hillary’s Des Moines Community Directors. “It’s more sophisticated than anything I could come up with. They have numbers that show that it’s eyes and ears, not feet that will win this race.”

Hillary for America Director James O’Brian showed us some of their work, demonstrating a map dividing Des Moines into 41 neighborhoods with their own specialized characteristics. In each of these neighborhoods, the campaign has several Neighborhood Team Leaders doing what they call “hyper-targeting”—using personalized text messages and phone calls to turn out voters, with occasional “direct in-person appeals.” O’Brian said each NTL had undergone and met a series of specific challenges the field organizers had presented.

(If you want more on Clinton’s unique ground game, check out Al Giordano’s blog, The Field.)

Whether Team Hillary’s high-tech approach to the campaign season remains to be seen, though Janice smiled as she told us about how the approach had yielded multiple, unofficial “satellite offices” from highly motivated supporters reached via text, phone, or social media. These volunteers were invited to meet with NTL for intensive training, derived from focus group experimentation, on the kinds of messages that might resonate with their voters.

With Hillary in town, the energy was less on these efforts and more on providing the candidate with an audience for her economic address. Since the economic downturn that began this summer with the popping of the housing bubble and near-failure of several major U.S. banks, Clinton has refocused her campaign less away from the domestic terror and foreign policy topics that are her clear preference toward what Secretary of Treasury Corzine has delightfully termed “food on table” issues, with the stalled healthcare reform drive and investments in high-tech industries forming the basis of that.

Enthusiastic support from volunteers notwithstanding, it’s unclear the degree to which this message is resonating with Iowa voters and others across the Midwest. Putting aside the lack of investment in the state from the Clinton camp (this is the first visit to a potential tipping point state in weeks, with most of the President’s focus being directed toward New Orleans and Chicago), neither the program nor the dysfunction a divided Washington brings much more than tepid crowds in this farm state.

Local Republicans have exploited spotty attendance to hold small protests outside campaign venues with a pantsless, lipstick-stained Bill Clinton impersonator—an attack that has dogged Hillary these past few years. Clinton Field Team Leader Ken Holland described the man’s appearance as “disheartening” when I pointed him out. “That Republicans, even with their nominee, disparage the first female president with these kinds of personal attacks is the height of misogyny.”

Nonetheless, it’s these kinds of troubles that make most Republicans regret sitting out this race during the primaries. Dole remains neck-and-neck (per Nate’s latest projections), but as the New York Times reported yesterday, large numbers of conservatives believe that their nominee’s views are out of step with the party overall, leading to dampening enthusiasm. More problematically, the presence of two women in the contest—while historically significant—is proving a real problem for Republicans trying to turnout male, conservative-leaning voters.

We’ll be following Elizabeth Dole’s campaign in Ohio tomorrow as it goes between Marietta and Athens. After that, we’ll rejoin the Clinton camp in Cleveland where she’ll be having her first major rally with her husband. We look forward to reporting to you then.

Huffington Post: Campaign Pre-Mortem: Dems Lifted By Kennedy’s Coattails, GOP Sinks Further Into the Crazy

Posted April 12, 2008 04:22 PM
By Arianna

Read More: [Martin Luther King Jr.], [Ted Kennedy], [Ron Paul], [George W. Bush]

On the eve of his historic health care vote, President Kennedy spoke to House Democrats. He began his remarks by invoking the memory of Martin Luther King, Jr.: “Of all the forms of inequality, injustice in health is the most shocking and inhumane.”

The moment cast in sharp relief the difference between the two parties. As Democrats lined up for floor speeches extolling a bill that would—after a yearlong process of negotiations and compromises—give Americans a public option and real care to millions, Republicans spent their time in lockstep opposition. The biggest question was not whether any Republican congressmen would support a bill destined to pass, but who would trot out the most outlandish and overwrought objection.

Indeed, as I watched this and other fights over the last three years, I’ve been reminded of another Martin Luther King quote, delivered as part of a sermon in 1963 as he struggled to advance the cause of the marginalized and dispossessed. It came amid similar, kneejerk opposition: “The ultimate measure of a man is not where he stands in moments of convenience and comfort, but where he stands at times of challenge and controversy.”

If we’re seeing this degree of opposition in times of unprecedented peace, with a good (albeit slowing) economy, and a popular president, what can we expect when times get tough? It’s enough to make you miss the good-natured bungling of early George W. Bush.

Today, the GOP is more radical than it has ever been. Since it evicted Bush and Cheney’s sycophants and installed Ron Paul’s lunatics, the party has picked fights it hasn’t needed to against people it can’t afford. It tried to draw out confirmation hearings against Justice Janet Reno and halt efforts to reform No Child Left Behind. It nearly derailed immigration reform with poison pill amendments, obstructed the National Education Trust Fund, and made hearings on trade agreements with China into highly televised circuses with their stunts.

Their toxic smokescreen of fear-mongering (immigrants are “invading our borders”; green energy investment “will bankrupt the country”) and cynical un-truths (Kennedy’s executive orders will “force gays into our churches”) reveal a party standing in the doorway of progress.

While many of the Democratic Party’s policies are deeply flawed (the rich have gotten richer, largely due to compromises between the White House and Blue Dogs) there’s no denying that the lives of millions of Americans will be improved because of what the Democrats have done. The agenda post-2008 looks to address the few problems that exist, starting with Kennedy’s promise to let Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of 2010.

Unless they return to sanity, the GOP risks sinking into further irrelevance. It would take a truly cataclysmic, earth-shattering development to reverse the gains of the last three years and Kennedy’s sky-high approval ratings (64% by Gallup’s last count).

So long as the sun keeps shining in Washington, the doom and gloom of nominee presumptive Paul is unlikely to appeal to more than the over-stimulated, online fringes.

What we need now are Republican leaders who can take inspiration from King and his words, who will approach issues decently and honestly. Far be it from me to praise George Bush, but now might be the time for a return to “compassionate conservatism.”

Too Much and Never Enough? Sen. Sanders Warns of Housing Bubble

The Shadow Cabinet

washingtonpost.com > Opinions
Wednesday, January 17, 2007

Who exactly is driving our foreign policy? It’s a fair question to ask, with President Ted Kennedy’s latest health scare giving him a week in Walter Reed Hospital. So far, Kennedy has focused primarily on domestic issues, passing an extensive healthcare bill and capping a midterm campaign with a breakthrough on immigration reform. But in the past 6 months, foreign crises have increasingly drawn his energy, whether in Darfur, the Caucasus, or the Levant, and above all, in these last two years of his first term—yes, he still intends to run for re-election—Kennedy will face the daunting prospect of winding down an ongoing war.

Yet the president seems entirely aloof, even absent, from the most important discussions taking place in the White House over how to manage the war. After the conflict in Lebanon last year, the potential for greater crises in the Middle East is high, and the risk of American troops being drawn in to a wider conflict is real. They’re already fighting in the region as is. Withdrawal plans have been scuttled, and the White House’s proposed exit timeline is fuzzy. But when Kennedy was asked about the war two weeks ago, he reiterated his campaign pledge to get “every American troop out.”

So which is it? The answer may lie in Kennedy’s top advisors. Eager to avoid the obvious comparisons to another President Kennedy’s “Best and Brightest” managing a war, these figures apparently are called “The Inner Circle” on the Washington cocktail circuit. Others prefer the term “Shadow Cabinet.” Much more innocuous.

A few of these top figures are not quite hiding in the shadows, but in fact have been publicly appointed by the president to fill vacant roles in the past 3 months. Wesley Clark earned widespread praise when he was selected to head the Defense Department, and everyone within a 100 mile radius of DC knows somebody who’s insisted to them that Richard Holbrooke’s childhood dream is to be Secretary of State. Others, however, have roles largely unknown to the public. Former Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is a frequent advisor, as is former Secretary of Defense William Perry.

Perhaps it’s terribly unremarkable that two top members of the last Democratic administration are advising the current Democratic administration, but senior officials tell me that Kennedy has relied on those two more than many inside the White House to direct foreign policy. Word is that his National Security Advisor hasn’t spoken to the president since the Russo-Georgian crisis last December, and before that, he hadn’t had a meeting with Kennedy in 3 months.

Even Sandy Berger, former Deputy National Security Advisor and current probationer, has been a leading voice inside the Inner Circle.

What do all these lifetime members of the foreign policy establishment have in common? Well, they all served in the Clinton administration, but more than that, they all remain in very close contact with another Clinton. It’s no secret that the New York Senator from Arkansas has had her eye on the presidency for years, and that at the slightest sign of Kennedy’s health worsening, she is sure to lead the pack in any Democratic primaries that ensue. But according to senior officials, she already has a heavy hand inside the White House. Albright and Holbrooke reportedly talk to her “near-daily” and Secretary Clark meets with her “several times a week.”

For many inside the Inner Circle, their standing in the Kennedy White House gives them a chance to fight old wars, and perhaps wage new ones. Bill Clinton famously called his inaction during the Rwandan genocide the gravest mistake of his presidency, and his top advisors have spent years living that down. Memoirs about Bosnia, Rwanda, and the failure in Somalia abound. One figure inside the White House told me, “they’re all about settling old scores from the Clinton years.”

So perhaps the best route in determining President Kennedy’s foreign policy strategy would be to ask what Hillary Clinton’s foreign policy strategy is. With withdrawal plans dashed, and calls for escalation growing, can we be sure that this Inner Circle will keep President Kennedy away from ramping up the war? Or will Hillary Clinton and her Shadow Cabinet be too eager to write their next memoirs?

2007 The Washington Post

Armored Vehicles Roll Over Iraq

wired.com
SECURITY | 11.03.07 | 2:36 PM

Since the end of the Cold War, the U.S. military has been talking up its new armored vehicles’ capabilities. In Iraq, you can spot vehicles, like the BAE Caiman, shuttling troops around from Basra to Baghdad. Fighting a seemingly intractable insurgency while simultaneously turning operations over to the Iraqi military, a spate of new Pentagon contracts have been signed to design more armored vehicles. The big problem? They keep running off the road.

According to a report in Jane’s Defense Weekly, virtually none of these vehicles can even drive properly. Dozens of instances of unresponsive steering, stuck wheels, and plain faulty engineering are cited. In one interview, a Marine who fought in Fallujah was highly critical. “I mean we’re driving this fucking thing and it just goes straight into a lake. Right off the bridge. It wasn’t high up either. It’s such bullshit.”

In Congressional hearings led by Sen. John McCain (R-AZ) last week on the withdrawal plans, lawmakers were shocked to hear how badly the vehicles have been performing. Statistics gathered from the Defense Department reported a 400% increase in accidents this year, the highest on record since 1969.

“Is the administration aware of how many accidents have occurred?” a stunned Sen. Jim Inhofe (R-OK) asked. When policy advisors from the Pentagon responded that they had briefed the White House on all recent developments in Iraq, Sen. McCain was incredulous. “If we can’t even build vehicles that can drive without going off the road, how can the administration expect us to withdraw so soon?”

According to Marines interviewed by Jane’s, the one highlight of these new armored vehicles are their bomb-proof doors. Casualties from IEDs set off by insurgents have actually decreased dramatically. But even this development is a double-edged sword.

REGIME CHANGE AT HARVARD

By Paul Atlantic
February 12, 2006

During icebreakers in my intro to comparative literature class, a student introduced himself as an “anti-imperialist,” before ever telling me his name. He discussed attending December’s so-called “National March on Washington” to “end the war.” This student then began to describe lurid conspiracy theories connecting the Bush family to terrorists with unpronounceable names. When I asked him where he learned this, he answered: a blog called “usscoletruth.”

I moved to another seat in my next class.

Iraq is a country with a population of 27.86 million people. It is 5,800 miles removed from Harvard. Yet the issue over whether Saddam Hussein poses a threat to the region and must be removed from power by an international coalition has torn apart this campus like no other. Few discuss the specifics of UN resolutions, President Clinton’s initial proposal to extend the no-fly zone, or how President Bush’s plans failed so spectacularly in Congress.

Instead, loud-mouthed trendsetters eager to meet girls and make friends with fellow self-proclaimed anti-imperialists shout that the military campaign closing in on Baghdad is a “war for oil.” Often they march across campus carrying signs that crudely depict Clinton and Vice President McCain as bloodthirsty warmongers. There is no room for nuance in this debate.

These protests are not just limited to Ivy League universities either. If opinion polls are anything to go by, Clinton has dismal numbers with young voters, even as her overall approval ratings tick up to the low-twenties. At a White House press conference last week, when the president was asked what she would say to voters feeling upset with both parties, she laughed, “Get over yourself!” Instant soundbite quality aside, it does lead many to wonder whether the administration understands the depth of anger over the war.

Yet despite these intense passions, few students have any connections to such far-away events. None of them are part of the force comprising 230,000 combat troops and many more contractors who have been deployed in Iraq. None of them have family who were gassed to death by the tyrant Saddam Hussein. None of them have been harmed by anthrax. They are merely spectators with no personal connections.

When I attended a moderately well-attended protest, I encountered a man in his thirties, not carrying any signs or banners, but participating in chants of “no blood for oil.” After he introduced himself as Salah, I asked him if he agreed with some of the speakers who had just called our own soldiers “baby-killers,” and whether that meant he wished violence upon them. He looked at me incredulously. “Are you serious?” Salah asked, voice rising. He proceeded to go on a rant about the death toll using figures from an American NGO called Iraq Body Count. In fact, the administration has strongly contested these reports, citing unspecified Pentagon documents that show lower death tolls, with Vice President McCain saying he doesn’t “believe the Iraqis are telling the truth about how many have been killed.”

Our interaction ended with Salah interrogating me over whether I had any personal connections to the region. When I told him no, he scoffed, and asked what I was doing here in the first place. “We’re talking about human beings. These are real people who are dying, this isn’t just some book report.”

Webster’s dictionary defines imperialism as “the actions by which one nation is able to control other usually smaller or weaker nations.” One has to ask whether such student activists are having the same effects on campus, cowing those who disagree into silence by putting up flyers in dorms and inviting extremists like Michael Moore to speak. Worst of all has been the failure of campus administrators, who have been either disastrously incompetent or working on behalf of other interests. Representative Eric Cantor’s widely seen hearings excoriating faculty at Ivy League schools rightly dominated headlines last month as the bombs begin to fall on Iraq, but far more needs to be done.

College administrators may not have wanted to wage a counterinsurgency on campus, but as former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld put it “you go to war with the army you have.”

A Portrait of Gephardt as More Continuity, Less Change

nytimes.com
Sept. 27, 2006

In Bob Woodward’s hotly anticipated new book, “Disarray,” President Gephardt is characterized as mercurial, indecisive, and even impulsive in his actions during the early months of his presidency. Like his predecessor, Mr. Gephardt emerges as a figure supremely confident in his own ability to shape history, casting aside advice to the contrary. This is hardly the candidate many thought they knew during the 2004 campaign, when the Democratic nominee campaigned on his competence and character, jabbing at President Bush for “not having the nerves” to steer the floundering mission in Iraq to some sort of success.

In Mr. Woodward’s gossipy yet highly readable account of a crucial point in the war, to the shock of many in the Bush administration’s transition team, Mr. Gephardt would change his mind on key issues multiple times in the same meeting. Intelligence briefers attempting to persuade the incoming president on the need for a new strategy to sort out the roiling Sunni-Shia sectarianism in Iraq were dismissed cavalierly. “It’s like deja vu,” one CIA analyst complained to Mr. Woodward.

Yet it would be a mistake to take these anonymous characterizations of the commander-in-chief at face value. Even senior officials participating in Mr. Gephardt’s war cabinet have only a limited understanding of the man and the difficult choices he faces, not only in Iraq but with the ongoing campaign in Afghanistan, the standoff over weapons inspectors in Iran, and rising tensions with Russia and China. Equal fault lies in the hands of the Coalition Provisional Authority in Baghdad, whose dismal handling of the post-dictatorship government has fueled the insurgency, according to a leaked intelligence report.

The book stays laser-focused on the White House however, with various officials castigating Gephardt’s advisors as “inept” and even “unqualified” for their duties. Mr. Woodward’s previous book, “Bush’s War,” vividly chronicled the debates leading up to the invasion of Iraq as well as serious doubts over the feasibility of a unilateral military campaign in Afghanistan. Many sources quoted in the previous book were withering in their criticism of Secretary of Defense Donald H. Rumsfeld, over his early role in prodding Mr. Bush towards deferring to military solutions in international relations.

The same can now be said of “Disarray,” which tears apart the carefully curated images of Mr. Gephardt’s top appointees. Secretary of Defense Wesley Clark is characterized as out-of-touch, with few firmly held beliefs, and presiding over a Pentagon more at war with itself than with the Iraqi insurgency. Secretary of State Richard Holbrooke is portrayed as a passive figure, unable or unwilling to restrain his deputies’ overreach, leading to ruinous relations between the U.S. and Nouri al-Maliki’s government in Iraq.

Above all, fundamental questions loom over the future of the coalition’s mission in Iraq. With a rudderless White House uninterested in pursuing any other course, Mr. Woodward’s book ends on a gloomy note. Reports circulating inside the intelligence community suggest that an enormous surge in the number of U.S. forces deployed to the country may be authorized as soon as next month, with the troop levels reaching even 200,000. Ironically, for all of Mr. Gephardt’s rhetoric about a “change in leadership,” this recommendation is right in line with what former Vice President Richard Cheney has been suggesting in interviews since late summer.

Mr. Woodward’s highly critical portrait of the president will provide ammo for both supporters and opponents of the war in Iraq alike, but Mr. Gephardt’s image as a decisive break from a chaotic predecessor will take the most damage. Pages of “Disarray” will remind many readers of Mr. Bush’s weakest qualities, and alarm those who expected more from the commander-in-chief. In one emblematic anecdote, Mr. Woodward recounts a meeting concerning signs that insurgents were regathering in Fallujah, which had been the site of the war’s fiercest fighting yet in November 2004. When C.I.A. Director James Clapper told the president bluntly that this suggested the coalition’s current strategy was not working, Gephardt blanched.

“He hasn’t even thought through the next day, let alone the next year,” Mr. Clapper said. “What Gephardt said was, in effect, That’s why we’ve got to stay the course. But there has been no debate over strategy, no serious discussion, it’s just been completely ignored.”

Correction: Sept. 29, 2006

The Books of The Times review on Wednesday, about “Disarray” by Bob Woodward, referred imprecisely to the number of Iraqi civilian casualties in the Iraq war. While the number of those killed estimated by the independent Iraq Body Count organization stands at 112,973, the number of casualties — killed, wounded and missing — as of Sept. 29 was 321,048.

President tosses press corps out of the ring

NewYorkMetro.com

Intelligencer Briefing
President tosses press corps out of the ring
‘Big Three’ CEOs release joint statement attacking ‘assault on the First Amendment’

By Jacob Bernstein

Like any good wrestling match, it ended with screaming and a shocking, attention-grabbing stunt. Leaning over the top of his lectern, his fingers pointing in accusation, President Jesse “The Brain” Ventura cut his own press conference short by announcing that he was tired of “jackals and jackasses” and expelling the White House Correspondents Association from the White House Grounds. Shocked reporters received 20 minutes to flee the briefing room before The Mind had them “removed.” Whether he or the Secret Service intended to do the “removing” was unclear.

For those in the Beltway, this latest brawl is a shock but not surprising. Since Ventura’s tumultuous elevation to the presidency three years ago, the president has made no secret of his loathing for the news media, using his podium and his “Weekly Webstreams” to call out specific commentators and pundits that he considers “in the tank for the powerful.”

In the week prior to the Press Room Blow-Up, President Ventura attacked New York Times commentator Judith Miller (“the mouthpiece of the people upstairs”), talk show host Bill Maher (“a smug, stupid son of a bitch”), and Fox commentator Bill O’Reilly (“spineless puke” and “a goose-stepping chickenhawk”). These attacks came on top of the president’s usual screeds against former Bush Administration officials, whom the president suggested “be brought before The Hague and executed” following revelations in the Administration’s recent Torture Report.

For DC area reporters, the feeling is mutual. The president has frequently been criticized for failing to hold court as previous presidents and cutting back on the pomp usually afforded to the esteemed members Fourth Estate.

“George Bush, he is not,” said one (former) press pool reporter from a major magazine. “I mean, with both Bill and George, they’d make an effort to get to know people and look for ways we could help each other. Whenever I’ve been in a room with Jesse, it feels like he’d rather be anywhere else.”

A reporter with the Washington Post, a focus of the president’s ire, was even more blunt: “He sent the Secret Service to my fucking house. They said that they had received a ‘tip’ that I’d ‘stolen’ dishware from Air Force One and could either return it or expect a bill for tens of thousands of dollars. I couldn’t believe it. Who fucking does that?”

While the closure of the Press Room will further limit the press’s access to the president, it is unlikely to stop the mountains of bad press. In the immediate aftermath of the expulsion, Roger Ailes of Fox, Rick Kaplan of MSNBC, and Philip Kent of CNN released a letter describing the president’s outburst as an ”assault on the First Amendment”, contributing a “chilling effect on the freedom of the press worldwide,” and fostering “a culture of fear not dissimilar from autocratic regimes like China.”

These will add to existing criticism about the president’s efforts to accelerate a pull-out from Afghanistan and Iraq, despite firm opposition from Speaker Cantor and Minority Leader Gephardt, as well as his unilateral and questionably legal closure of the detention center at Guantanamo Bay.

Government too remains predictably choked with gridlock, with most cabinet offices held by career officials. Though hearings have been scheduled for Ventura’s “VA for All” health plan, the overall proposal has been harshly criticized by the Times editorial board as well as various doctor’s groups for “socializing medicine.” A recent poll from Gallup found Ventura’s support at a mere 39.2%, with many criticizing his excessive use of Executive Orders to achieve priorities.

But perhaps none of this matters to the president. Asked two weeks ago about his low approval and the improbability of re-election, “The Mind” responded in his usual manner.

“Don’t care. Are you going to ask me a question that people care about or are you planning to just waste more of my time?”

Project for the New American Century: “Why Afghanistan Failed: A Forum Discussion”

Last month, the Ventura Administration released a slight, unsigned report titled, “The US Withdrawal from Afghanistan.” The report tries to put a pleasant spin on the otherwise chaotic 2007 withdrawal, praising President Ventura for “unilaterally ending an unjust war,” for participating in “intensive and rigorous deliberations through the interagency process,” and “reckoning with the costs and benefits of his options.”

This document does not, at any point, mention the numerous reports before or after the withdrawal of the potentially “cataclysmic” consequences if US officials abandoned Central Asia’s fledgling democracy. It does not mention the estimated 26 million Afghans now dealing with a repressive regime in the form of a restored and reinvigorated Taliban. It does not mention the human rights crisis created as a result of the Taliban’s restrictions on women’s ability to work or the new threat that the country poses in the form of radicalized young men seeking “revenge” on the United States for the invasion. It does not mention the continued fights that the president has had with Congress for his “unilateral” decision-making, subsequent efforts to restrain his reckless foreign policy, or investigations over his misuse of defense funds for pet infrastructure projects.

The president’s reckless decision-making raises serious questions about the ability of the US to stay the course on Iraq. After countless sacrifices and billions of dollars in aid and support for nation building, the United States could very easily wind up back at Square One, setting the stage for a new tyrant to emerge. Congress has acted by proactively binding the president’s hands but real security will only emerge when we grapple with the kind of commander-in-chief that Ventura is and why he allowed these failures to take place.

The Platinum Coin explained

washingtonpost.com
Wednesday, June 1, 2005

President Robert Byrd proclaimed early this evening that he had pulled the U.S. government from the brink of an unprecedented default through the minting of a $1 trillion coin, catching everyone from futures traders to congressional leaders off guard. Here’s what you need to know about the shock development.

What’s been going on in Washington?

During the 2004 election, President Byrd made support for a balanced budget and opposition to former President Bush’s wars in Iraq and Afghanistan centerpieces of his campaign. Once in office, he sought to move this agenda forward through his administration’s so-called “Constitution Budget,” which aimed to put the U.S. back on a path to fiscal solvency through aggressive cuts to the defense budget. Despite staunch opposition from both Republicans and many members of his own party, the President has insisted on these cuts, as well as funding for withdrawals from the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, as part of any major yearly spending bill he would sign.

Under most circumstances, the worst consequences of such a standoff would be a government shutdown, much like the ones 1995 and 1996. However, the specifics of U.S. federal spending rules make this confrontation between Byrd and Congress exponentially more urgent than prior budget disputes. 2005’s major spending bills were set to include a raising of the debt limit — the statutory limit of the amount of money the government is allowed to borrow — making it so that Byrd would be unable to veto any budgets without his desired cuts without risking the federal government going bankrupt.

While the White House repeatedly requested that Congress pass a bill solely focused on raising the debt limit so budgetary negotiations could proceed without the threat of bankruptcy looming over them, Congressional leaders from both parties demurred, maintaining that any raising of the debt limit should be passed at the same time as the overall federal budget.

What is the Platinum Coin?

The idea is that the President orders the treasury secretary to mint a $1 trillion coin out of platinum, then deposit it at the Federal Reserve. Then, just like that, the government would have an additional $1 trillion to pay off its obligations. The debt ceiling is no longer an issue. So, it’s just that: a literal coin, made out of platinum, with a value of $1 trillion.

Why platinum? The Treasury is limited by law on how much paper money and gold, silver and copper coins it can circulate at once. But due to an obscure law from the 1990s. there’s no limit on how many platinum coins it can circulate, or on their value.

What is on the Platinum Coin?

According to the Treasury, the coin uses an existing press of the US Constitution, which had been used in several gold dollar coins.

Does President Byrd own the Platinum Coin?

No. Despite the President’s proclamation at his press conference that “big daddy’s got a big coin,” it is the property of the Treasury Department.

Where is the Platinum Coin?

The Platinum Coin was last seen in President Byrd’s suit jacket, where he appeared to wave it around before laughing. The Department of Treasury has yet to comment.

How will this affect the standoff between Byrd and Congress over the withdrawal?

Reactions on the Hill have been divided between outrage, confusion and horror. Party leaders, nearing the end of an exhausting, week-long negotiation process to craft a budget without the White House’s involvement, were both at a loss as to how to proceed. A source close to Speaker Richard Gephardt expressed frustration that their boss’s extensive efforts to pry more left-leaning members of his party away from the President’s position will be undone without the threat of a default.

Members of the congressional minority expressed anger, bordering on rage, across the board. One high-ranking source close to Senate Minorty Leader Rick Santorum fumed that “that old fucking man” had just “fucked everything up,” further commenting that “we can’t do anything now. He won. Of course that goddamn cryptkeeper remembered some shit like this.”

What happens next?

Experts called in for quotes were at a loss for how things would proceed following the President’s pronouncement. A source with a background in coinage law asked to comment for this story was silent for roughly a minute before saying, “Well, I suppose it’s technically legal,” although making sure to emphasize that the Supreme Court will have the final say. Speaking off the record, a high-ranking employee at a major multinational bank summed up the feeling on Wall Street: “I genuinely have no idea what the economic consequences are. I’m not sure if the credit rating will be downgraded. This isn’t supposed to be happening”

Market futures were down across the board after the press conference. Attempts to reach Federal Reserve Chair Alan Greenspan through his official communication channels have so far been met without comment.

America’s Democracy is in Deep Danger | Opinion

nytimes.com
April 13, 2006

Seize the military. Bombard the presidential palace. Topple the sitting leader. Take over the media. This is how we think of authoritarian regimes beginning. Yet democracy often dies in the light, as Smith and Hart, professors of government at Harvard, write in their comprehensive, enlightening and terrifyingly timely new book, The Demagogue’s Playbook. Written as an ironic imitation of Machiavelli’s The Prince, the authors make the trenchant point that democracies may die at the hands not of generals but of elected leaders.

Smith and Hart lay out a four-part test for identifying authoritarian leaders: rejecting democratic decision-making, denying the legitimacy of political opponents, tolerating or encouraging violence and engaging in conspiracy theories. “With the exception of Richard Nixon, no major-party presidential candidate met even one of these four criteria over the last century,” they note. “Robert Byrd met all of them.”

How so? It’s a story that may be recognizable to Times readers who followed the 2004 presidential campaign, but the dire importance of the moment commands us to re-tell it nonetheless. Rejecting democratic decision-making: an easy call. When speaking to large crowds of college students on the campaign trail, Byrd repeatedly referred to President Bush’s decision to topple Saddam Hussein’s regime as “illegal,” despite the fact that it was approved by Congress. Denying the legitimacy of political opponents? Another easy one: Vice President Conyers objected to Bush’s certification as President before he was even sworn in. Tolerating and encouraging violence may be more subtle, but one need only watch his rallies to see the angry, black-or-white, downright anti-democratic attitudes of his young supporters.

But it is this last point— conspiracy theories—that may be the most concerning of them all. To understand why, just look at one of the principal comparative examples that Smith and Hart bring up in their book: Venezuela. High in the American public consciousness since the Freedomista uprisings against the Chavez regime in 2005, the story of how the country’s disputed president came to power serves as the author’s principal guides Still writing as ostensive advisors, they show how “El Commandante” ascended to his throne: casting the existing political class as a corrupt, self-interested establishment, alleging a vast foreign conspiracy to keep the country down, and re-orienting politics around impossible, feel-good goals like “ending poverty” instead of targets that follow the economic consensus.

Byrd’s rhetoric on the campaign trail in 2004, his invectives against “Poppy’s boy” and all, fit this guide so perfectly that it makes one wonder if he received an advance copy of it. But it is his statements from the White House in recent weeks, which occurred after the publishing of this book, that makes one think that either the authors are downright prescient or that the President wishes to mock them. During his opening remarks at an event awarding the Presidential Medal of Freedom to filmmaker Michael Moore, he alluded to countless conspiracy theories, from a joke that he “paid for the event with Rummy’s funds” to alleging that “Junior” would have “given this award to a Saudi Arab” were he still in office.

With many Americans still struggling to get their heads around these endless displays of disrespect, Smith and Hart provide a valuable way of understanding what their purpose may be. President Byrd, it seems, knows exactly what he is doing, and nothing is as it seems. His sanctimonious paeans to the constitution disguise a long-running disdain for it. His proposed budgets lacking funds for the Freedomistas do not come from a desire to balance the budget, but from a sympathy with a kindred spirit in Caracas. If any of the Times’s readers are parents of the children who gave Byrd his victory in 2004, consider sending them this book. The future of democracy may depend on it.

Mugglenet Dot Com

Mugglenet Dot Com » The Department of Mysteries: Voldemir Putin and George W. Fudge
by MuggleNet · Published August 12, 2008

Jo Rowling is in Washington today to receive the Presidential Medal of Freedom, a high honor that celebrates the publication of her final book in the saga, “Harry Potter and the Doomspell Sorcerer.”

While she’s touched millions around the globe (over 500 million, according to latest book sales), her success is more than that. Part of Jo’s brilliance is the way she ties in the characters and events of her fantasy world into Our World. Harry Potter is more than just a book series—it’s a guide to live and interpret society, like Marcus Aurelius’s Meditations. That fact has been picked up by some of the world’s most powerful people.

In this blog, I want to talk about the top three moments where Harry Potter showed its power to shape world events. By the time you read this, who knows, maybe there’ll be another one to add!

#3 Dumbledore’s Online Army

It started off small during the campaign. Outraged by the small-mindedness and bigotry of Bush, hundreds of Potterheads came together to mobilize an underground resistance against him. They wrote blogs giving people tips on how to talk to their friends and parents about the election. They made posters comparing Bush to Cornelius Fudge, Minister of Magic, who did his best to focus people’s outrage on the crazy coot Dumbledore, the attention-seeking Harry, and everything else except the real menace at large (that’s the Evil Axis)!

When Bush and Dick “Umbridge” Cheney (they’re both short and fat, hehehe) got “sacked”, Potterheads launched a new chapter of the movement. Calling themselves as “Dumbledore’s Online Army” (Clark = Dumbledore, the voice of truth) they started trawling the Web and the meatworld to take the fight to the trolls, liars, and haters out there.

And it looks like they got noticed! After thwarting the Code Pink Death Eaters outside the WH, First Lady Gertrude was spotted carrying her copy of “Half Blood Prince.” Even Clark’s Secretary of State Powell got in on the fun—showing off his family’s Potter-themed Halloween costumes on Facebook!!! Not even the Recession could spoil the fun, as Secretary Nunn urged Americans to “keep up their spirits and not let sorrow win”!

It’s messages like these that show, from Day One, someone in the White House was watching closely. In the words of Albus himself, “It is important to fight and fight again, and keep fighting, for only then can evil be kept at bay though never quite eradicated.”

#2 The Uzbek Potter Rebellion

A message throughout the series is that young people have the power to change the world. In Harry Potter, the students of Dumbledore’s Army were as much at the forefront of the Resistance as the Order of the Phoenix. This activism was praised in Harry Potter and in our own world. In the wise words of Albus Dumbledore, “Age is foolish and forgetful when it underestimates youth.”

It is also present in smaller acts of activism. Even though her world seemed complex, Hermione didn’t let SPEW get swatted down by jeers that “it’s not that simple.” She worked hard to free the house-elves of abuse and ensure they could continue to serve others with joy.

In 2006, the little-known and forgotten country of Uzbekistan found its own Hermione Granger in the form of Galima Bukharbaeva. A journalist, Bukharbaeva reported on the Uzbek government’s attacks on young, unarmed protestors—sort of like how the Death Eaters attacked defenseless students at Hogwarts. These reports earned the attention of President Clark who vowed America would not “stand aside” and allow violence and authoritarianism to spread and clamp down on the free spread of ideas. Dumbledore’s Online Army answered his call.

Over the course of a year, DOA activists raised money to send thousands of guns and Harry Potter books to Uzbekistan to break the government’s stranglehold on people’s minds. Some traveled to Andjian to distribute wands and messages of Resistance. (“It’s one short step from ‘Wizards first’ to ‘Purebloods first,’ then to ‘Death Eaters.’”) Others did what they could to fight against Uzbek Quibblers by helping out local groups like the IMU and HUT—groups that might sound scary but want to help people, just like SPEW does.

The battle against the Karimov regime remains incomplete. Unfortunately it and many other Central Asian countries have fallen into civil war, but DOA and other Potterhead organizations have joined Clark in spearheading a global uprising against tyrants worldwide.

WHO’S WINNING, WHO’S LOSING, AND WHY

SLATE > NEWS & POLITICS

POLITICS: WHO’S WINNING, WHO’S LOSING, AND WHY

How to Fix Airport Security
The results of Slate’s reader contest.

BY JENNY ROGERS
Jan 3, 2008

Today marks the one-year anniversary of the formation of the Department of Homefront Affairs and the Transportation Security Agency. In that time there have been reports in that time about airline passengers’ experiences and the new Agency’s many, many growing pains—from missed flights to sexual harassment to allegations of biased screenings to lawsuits over invasions of privacy and violations of civil liberties. While we can all agree with President Hart that some type of security reform was necessary, especially in light of recent reports of thwarted attacks, there’s little consensus on how to make our airports safer.

Last week, we asked Slate readers for their ideas on how to improve the Agency at a time of mounting anger and frustration. We received more than 400 submissions, which were evaluated by Slate associate editor Chris Wilson and an all-star panel of judges: Tom Ridge, former Governor of Pennsylvania and current head of the Ridge Consulting Group; Jane Harman, former member of the US House of Representatives and current member of the President’s Commission on Asymmetrical Threats; and General Wesley Clark, former SACEUR and current contestant on the reality television program “Dancing with the Stars.” (Read the judges’ full bios here.)

The ideas our panel reviewed ranged from the absurd (replace all fluorescent airport lighting with soothing mood lighting) to the obscene (make people undress and go barefoot through airport security) to the downright invasive (subject all passengers to full-body scans). A surprising number of readers suggested strapping passengers into planes and arming flight crews, which might make us never fly again. Another took example from the president and suggested that we “get communities involved” by allowing bored Americans to watch live streams of security footage and flag anyone who looks shady.

After sifting through all submissions, our panel selected four winning entries, which you can read below. We will forward their full proposals to the TSA, Congress, and White House. Thanks to all who participated.

Fourth Place: Remake Our Airports for the 21st Century: Jesse Smith of Montana believes that recent government modernization efforts shouldn’t stop at IT but physical infrastructure as well. “With the revival of the Office of Technology Assessment, the President and Congress have undertaken a multi-billion-dollar effort to update America’s computers, networks, and intranet systems. However, our obsession with ‘cyberspace’ threatens our real, physical infrastructure,” she writes. “Congress urgently needs to fund improvements to America’s deteriorating airports, train stations, and highways. We cannot continue to rely on buildings built in 1950 for 21st century problems.” The judges liked Smith’s specific examples drawing from the European Union and, in particular, Germany. One judge joked he was in favor of any proposal that allowed them to bulldoze JFK. (Read the full text of Jesse Smith’s entry.)

Third Place: Tie TSA Funding to Ward Scoring: Ari Cohen of New Hampshire proposes relying on the Hart Administration’s “Community Ward” grant program to link TSA funding to public approval. “No one knows their airports like the people who live around them,” Flescher reasons. “By decentralizing funding to communities—what some call ‘participatory budgeting’—we can ensure that TSA divisions in high-functioning cities are rewarded and those lagging behind get the scrutiny they need. Call it ‘No Airport Left Behind.’” Judges were impressed by how this proposal could tie into the Hart Administration’s existing priorities, but one judge worried that it might overburden a pilot program that has seen little expansion outside blue states and is already overburdening small towns with additional forms and bureaucracy. (Read the full text of Ari Flescher’s entry.)

Second Place: Expand Social Media Monitoring for Extremist Content: Carla McCartney and Phil Kasparov of Washington, DC wanted to see G-Men update to the modern age. “‘Precogs’ are no longer the domain of science fiction. With MySpace, The Face Book, and LiveJournal, we have ever-greater insight into what terrorists think and how they operate,” they explain. “While the Department of Homefront Affairs is charged with defending our cyber infrastructure, the bipartisan FREEDOM Act doesn’t go far enough in giving our intel agencies visibility. Websites that operate in the United States should be required to provide data on suspected extremists to airlines and to the government.” Judges thought this idea was forward-thinking, especially given the increasingly radical rhetoric and attempted bombings in some Central Asian countries. (Read the full text of Carla McCartney and Phil Kasparov’s entry.)

First Place: Expand the Drone Program: Finally, Brenda Lovett of Texas received full marks from our panel for identifying the problem at its root. “The Hart Administration should be lauded for making big investments in tech, investments that have yielded rapid improvements in so-called ‘unmanned aerial vehicles’ or ‘drones’ for surveillance and defense. These tools allow America to promote international security around the world, without having to put soldiers in harm’s way. We have already seen its effectiveness in places like Yemen, Somalia, and Afghanistan, where it has been used to conduct surgical strikes on terrorists who would seek harm against the United States,” Brenda states. “However, threats in these countries only grow day by day, with growing attacks on American aid workers and tourists. The only way to ensure our safety is to expand the use of armed drones to disrupt terrorist hot spots and eliminate those who support them.” Judges were wowed by this proposal, noting how drones could fundamentally alter warfare and counterterrorism. One judge noted that this tool could easily be expanded to address adversarial regimes like that of North Korea, whose saber-rattling in 2004 almost provoked a major confrontation. Indeed, this proposal has already been adopted, in part, by leading Republican candidate Donald Rumsfeld. (Read the full text of Brenda Lovett’s entry.)

Recovered 39th Tovane, 1030 P.D.


Item Identification
: Artifact 68A-33C

Classification
: Religious Object

Estimated Period
: Pre-Cataclysm Era I (PCE I)

Material Composition
: Painted aluminum, plastic/vinyl, glass (suspected), other unidentified material

Item Description
: What you are looking at now is a rarity among Plastic Era artifacts—an almost fully intact Terrune Box. Referred to varyingly by indigenous tribes as a “löptöp,” a “pewter” device, or a “black mirror,” very few fully intact Terrune Boxes have been recovered by archeologists. Many were destroyed in the Great Deluge or abandoned in its immediate aftermath. This device was discovered during the settlement and pacification of Old Usaya by a local farmer who discovered it buried within a box, wrapped in several layers of aluminum and plastic material. This museum greatly appreciates its subsequent donation.

Historians intensely debate the purpose of Terrune Boxes. Varying legends connect them to communication, entertainment, music, and the arts. These stories are considered largely without merit, likely the product of local superstitions and misunderstandings. Based on recovered scraps of Plastic Era artwork, their mass production in the period immediately preceding the Great Deluge, and the title “black mirror,” many historians suspect that Terrune Devices served some kind of religious purpose, possibly the centerpiece of a shrine. This is further supported by the ornate, colorful blue and green patterns located within the aluminum device and their mass abandonment after the Great Deluge. For those who saw the cataclysm, it must have truly seemed that the gods had abandoned them!

This Terrune Box is particularly unusual in that its one-time owner appears to have emblazoned several additional religious and political icons on its exterior. Only two other Terrune Devices with these markings have been discovered. Below we provide translations of each of the stickers from Plastic Era English to the common tongue as well as what historians think they might have represented. From right to left:

1. STOP THE KOREAN WAR!: This icon is widely believed to be an intercession to the gods for victory against the ancient tribe of Korea. The Usayan civilization and its warlords were involved in a conflict with the Korean people and their allies shortly before the Great Deluge. The outcome of this conflict remains a mystery.

2. CLARK, FOUR MORE WARS!: A similar intercession to the gods, celebrating the triumphs of the final Usayan leader, a conqueror known as “Clark,” and appealing for additional triumphs.

3. ALL IS WELL: A celebration of prosperity in the period immediately prior to the Great Deluge. The conqueror Clark is portrayed in a three-fourths view before what is thought by historians to be a scale of justice or modified cross (an ancient religious symbol). Also behind Clark is a bright red cloud, an allusion to his military triumphs.

4. “IDIOTS”: Plastic Era English word for “IDIOTS” represented with the symbols of various mystery cults prominent during the period. This icon has been the subject of substantial debate among historians. While some historians argue that it was meant in a mocking tone—to castigate the enemies of the Usayan civilization—recovery of similarly represented icons arrayed in the shape of the Old Plastic English word “COEXIST” suggest the phrase could have some as-of-yet undiscovered positive context.

5. FSM: The Plastic Era English letters "FSM" within some kind of stylized creature. The purpose of this symbol remains unclear and is heavily debated by historians.

6. “FRUIT OF KNOWLEDGE”: Unlike the other icons on this Terrune Box, the Fruit of Knowledge has been carved instead of painted, suggesting great importance. The fruit with a bite taken from it alludes to an ancient creation myth in which an apple containing knowledge of good and evil was given to humanity. The Fruit of Knowledge symbol appears of several other recovered Terrune Boxes, suggesting this myth was of central importance for the civilizations of the period.

7. “FALLING ANGEL”: A common symbol of Plastic Era art, depicting a falling angel. Often found in centers of learning and worship sites, it is believed by many historians to be a symbol of good luck and prosperity.

8: “SACRIFICIAL ANIMAL”: A stylized creature (possibly a horse or cattle). Positioned atop the falling angel, it may be intended as a stylized offering to appease the gods and help bring victory over the people of Korea.

9: GOT OIL?: References to “oil” appear in many surviving texts from the Plastic Era and the oral traditions of local cultures. “Oil” here may refer to either a sacramental oil—which would make sense given the religious context of many of the other icons on this box and the great emphasis many writings give the substance.

10: “PILLARS OF HEAVEN”: The meaning of this symbol remains unclear but has been referred to by many historians as the “pillars of heaven”.

Years after the 2004 election, a D.C. mystery unravels

washingtonpost.com
Wednesday, March 24, 2012

It goes without saying that the 2004 presidential election was a race unlike any other. Just the matchup by itself—a well-respected wartime president against an anti-war octogenarian institution of the Senate—would have been enough to put it in the history books. But of all the race’s twists and turns, perhaps the most dramatic was the definitive moment of its election night: President Bush’s unprecedented victory in the District of Columbia.

Even those who were the most optimistic about the size of the President’s potential victory hadn’t penciled in a win there, and for good reason. Not only had every single Democratic presidential candidate won D.C. since it had been given the right to vote in presidential elections before 2004, none had ever received less than 70% of the vote. The District also quickly returned to form thereafter, giving Senator Joe Biden 85% of the vote in his losing 2008 presidential bid. Even if you look at the local level, you’ll still be hard-pressed to find any precedents for Bush’s vote, with the closest possibly being the 1994 mayoral race where District Republicans won 41% of the vote—and still lost. And while Byrd did do uniquely poorly across the country’s urban areas (for obvious reasons), none of those drop offs from 2000 came even close to what he faced in Washington.

To put it simply: what the hell happened?

In the immediate aftermath of the election, it was hard to get answers. Democratic operatives in the city were, perhaps understandably, tight-lipped about what had occurred, although they did appear curiously indifferent about the biggest humiliation for the city party in its history. But now that many of those same staffers have moved on to new jobs, new places, and even new parties, they’re starting to open up about what happened. And the picture that they’re putting together is one that may have one Robert C. Byrd spinning at mach 9 in his grave at Arlington National Cemetery.

To put it simply once again: they were in on it.

The distaste, even disgust, members of the Democratic establishment felt towards Byrd during the 2004 election was well-known, even at the time. Those who were willing to accept his racist past couldn’t get over him being anti-war, and those who were willing to accept him being anti-war couldn’t get over his racist past. It led to breakdowns in party support for his ticket across the country. Nowhere was this more acute than in D.C., where staffers and volunteers alike disagreed with Byrd on both aspects of his campaign. Some ghosted the entire election season. Many more volunteered for third parties more aligned with their sensibilities. But for the cream of the crop of D.C.’s local political class, the destination of choice was standing by the President—both covertly and overtly.

I spoke to one of these double-agent staffers, now an executive for Facebook, about why so many of his peers made this decision. Speaking off the record, he told me that it was a combination of principle and self-interest. “Let’s be real,” he said. “None of us were really with the old man on the war. Our delegation was unanimous for Clark for a good reason. Add in what the feelings were at the places we wanted to work for—look. At a certain point, it starts to look better if you weren’t part of the process that got that old racist his only electoral votes outside of West Virginia. So, yeah, we met up with those guys in our frats who worked for the other team. We gave them some funds, same as we did with the third parties. Some of us even knocked on some doors for them. Pretty much everyone knew what was going on at the time. Honestly, I’m just surprised the results have been taken at face value for so long.”

So, a turncoat party infrastructure. Money being sent to D.C. from the DNC and the Byrd campaign finding its way in the hands of the enemy. The best hands doing field work for the other side. Still, even this doesn’t explain why 2004’s nominee did so poorly. And what did this former staffer mean by “taking things at face value”?

“Look, you know, it’s not nice,” he said. “But this is how it’s always been done. Lyndon Johnson was one of our greatest presidents and he did it all the time. We just couldn’t—we couldn’t let the city get embarrassed, all right? We couldn’t have been the last ones voting for that man. It’s not like it made a difference. And, besides, you know, when you do that, those people just weren’t voting anyways, right? They already didn’t like him. There were major drops in turnout. What was the harm in making that a little more explicit?”

Twin Peaks Season Two Revisited: The Hidden Genius of the Ben Horne Civil War Subplot

vanityfair.com
May 19, 2005

If you ask a dedicated fan of Twin Peaks, the hit 1990’s murder-mystery TV show by David Lynch and Mark Frost, what they think of the show’s second season, you’re likely to hear an earful. A little over ten years after its cancellation, the series’ dropoff in quality after Lynch departed mid-season in anger over being forced to reveal Laura Palmer’s killer early has already become the stuff of TV legend. Lacking a clear sense of purpose and direction, the Lynch-less writers bored away millions of views with infamously aimless subplots. Even Lynch’s last-second return to direct the critically acclaimed series finale wasn’t enough to save it from cancellation mere months after it was the biggest show in America.

I’m not going to defend most of these plots here. If you want to find someone willing to defend the merits of James Hurley’s mopey out-of-town adventures and the saga of Super Nadine, High School Wrestling Superstar!, you’ll have to read another review. Instead, I’m here to revisit one of the more forgotten plotlines that the showrunners tried out after the central mystery was revealed: Benjamin Horne’s Civil War-themed descent into insanity, wherein he gets so invested in re-enacting the Battle of Gettysburg that he comes to believe that he is Robert E. Lee.

In case you need a spoiler warning for a 14-year-old show, stop here.

Now, what drives Ben to this point? To put it short, he goes through quite a lot over the first season-and-a-half of the show. Introduced as the town’s local bigwig closing in on a big international deal, practically everything goes downhill for him as the main investigation of the show is carried out. It’s after this when he goes all-in on Civil War mania: reenacting battles, dressing up in full Rebel garb, and refusing to speak to his family and associates unless they play along. Ben’s re-enactments are also decidedly ahistorical. He begins by having the Confederates triumph at Gettysburg and follows their victories all the way to a conquest of Washington, D.C. And according to the show’s Dr. Jacoby, this process is entirely necessary. By rewriting American history, he experiences rewriting his own history, too. It all culminates in him finally coming back to his senses after a climatic “victory,” after which he becomes a (seemingly) changed man.

A desperate attempt to ape Lynch’s absurdist tendencies…or a roadmap for what would happen over the next ten years of American politics?

Think about it. The showrunners didn’t just choose anyone in the town of Twin Peaks to become infatuated with the Confederacy. They specifically chose one man who had found himself face-first in the dirt after facing loss after loss. Now, think about who this may have represented in American politics of the 1990s. Anti-war activists, steamrolled by both Republicans and Democrats united on foreign intervention. Liberals, forced to abandon their long-held priorities as both parties adopted a center-right consensus. Average Americans in factory towns from the Great Lakes to the Carolinas, forced to watch their communities destroyed as corporations shipped their livelihoods overseas. All some of the biggest losers in this country—and all the biggest constituencies for one Robert C. Byrd’s shocking presidential run last year.

Unlike Ben, there’s no reason for me to go over Byrd’s past. Republicans did a perfectly fine job making sure we knew all about his old controversial associations over the past year. This simultaneous existence of his 1944 activities and 2004 campaign was always covered as something of a paradox. How, many asked, could so many of this country’s most left-leaning constituencies, from students to union workers to regular old liberals, be so enamored with this relic of the Old South? Twin Peaks suggests that it wasn’t in spite of his connection to the Confederacy, but possibly even because of it. When you’re an American who has been out-maneuvered time and time again, utterly crushed by an opposition that seems to always find the better of you, how can you not see yourself in the greatest losing cause in the history of this country—the so-called Lost Cause itself?

“Wait,” some of you might say. “Ben Horne is no bleeding heart. He was the town’s foremost ruthless capitalist.” I’d agree—if you were talking about the Ben Horne we knew at the start of the show. But here’s the kicker. By the end of the series, Ben has turned over a new leaf, taking up causes like environmental protection and allying with groups in Seattle. In other words: a liberal, not unlike many who steered Robert Byrd’s campaign through the primaries. It’s worth considering that the writers were making a big point here with how easily he adopted these beliefs right after adopting a persona as Robert E. Lee. Perhaps those two strains of American political life may have a connection deeper than many imagined, at least before Byrd, like those HBO studio executives, revealed the mystery for us.

Broadway World Dot Com: AMERICAN PSYCHO! on Broadway - A Complete Guide

Broadway World Dot Com: AMERICAN PSYCHO! on Broadway - A Complete Guide

Get all the details you need about the show making a killing on Broadway

Looking for information about one of the hottest shows on Broadway? BroadwayWorld has the scoop on all you need to know about Patrick Bateman’s Broadway killing spree. Details below!

Where is AMERICAN PSYCHO! playing on Broadway?

AMERICAN PSYCHO! is running on Broadway at the Winter Garden Theatre. The Winter Garden Theatre is a Broadway theater at 1634 Broadway in the Theatre District of Midtown Manhattan in New York City.

How do I get to AMERICAN PSYCHO! on Broadway?

To arrive by subway, take the 1 to 50th Street or the N, R, or W to 49th Street. The Winter Garden Theatre is on Broadway between 50th and 51st Streets.

When did AMERICAN PSYCHO! open on Broadway?

AMERICAN PSYCHO! began previews on October 18, 2011 and opened on November 14, 2011, then-starring Josh Groban as Patrick Bateman, Andrew Rannells as Paul Owen / Detective Kimball, and Britney Spears as Courtney / Jean. It received mostly positive reviews on first opening, with many praising the cast and politically conscious script. The New York Times praised it in its review “Age of Avarice,” which characterized its satire of America’s “corrupt, business-obsessed culture of excess” as “a breath of fresh air.”

Is AMERICAN PSYCHO! playing outside of New York City?

Yes! AMERICAN PSYCHO! is currently touring the US and has productions running in the West End, China, and Korea. Touring productions are currently running in Australia and Germany with a Middle Eastern debut planned to debut in Abu Dhabi later this year (with mild alterations to accommodate censorship).

What is AMERICAN PSYCHO! based on?

AMERICAN PSYCHO! is very loosely based on the controversial 1991 novel American Psycho by Bret Easton Ellis and the 2000 film of the same name starring Christian Bale.

What is AMERICAN PSYCHO! about?

Set in Wall Street during the investment boom of the 1980s, AMERICAN PSYCHO! depicts the daily life and struggles of a young investment banker named Patrick Bateman. While Patrick masks himself as a suave and compassionate “problem solver” by day, he spends his nights consumed by feelings of inadequacy, rage, anxiety, and bloodlust. Through his rampage through the shallow and superficial world of Manhattan, the audience learns about Patrick’s feelings of contempt toward a distant and disapproving father, his antipathy toward the corporate “yuppies” who will never accept him, and his deep-seated hatred toward women and minorities. The more he succeeds, the more empty he feels.

The bitingly satirical production won 8 Tony Awards and a Grammy. It features a book by Dave Malloy and music and lyrics by Duncan Sheik and Trent Reznor.

What are some of the popular songs in AMERICAN PSYCHO?

AMERICAN PSYCHO features a number of Billboard-charting songs by its award-winning cast. These songs, which range from pop to 80s-inspired synth beats, include “Cards,” “Idea of Me,” “Because I Love You,” “Lethal,” and “No Exit.” It also features covers of “Hip to Be Square” and “In the Air Tonight.”

Owing to its international success, AMERICAN PSYCHO is heading toward the big screen next summer with a cast that includes Ansel Elgort, Armie Hammer, and Katerina McCrimmon. First-time director Hugh Jackman hopes that the film will bring AMERICAN PSYCHO to a new audience while preserving the “anti-greed message that audiences everywhere have come to love.”

It has been rated PG-13.
