Royal wins French presidential election

Le Monde with AP and AFP
6 May 2007

Ségolène Royal, candidate of the Socialist Party, was elected president of France on Sunday, May 6th, with 61% of the vote compared to 39% for her rival, Jean-Marie Le Pen. Ms. Royal’s victory makes her France’s first female president and its first socialist leader since François Mitterrand.

Royal’s ascension is a triumphless victory for her and her party, expected by all and celebrated by few. Indeed, most attention during the campaign has gone to her opponent, Mr. Le Pen, made internationally infamous in his ascension to the second round of the 2002 election. In that race, the mere shock of Mr. Le Pen’s narrow second-place victory in the first round was considered a national disgrace. This time, a repeat second-round ascension was considered guaranteed for the past year. The only question was how far he could go in the runoff. The answer, it seems, was quite far indeed.

While Mr. Le Pen did not quite meet the numbers some late surveys predicted he would — with most ballots counted, he seems set to fall just short of the 40% mark — his total represents a massive shift in French politics since 2002. Back then, all of French society united around President Jacques Chiraq in a bid to keep Le Pen’s numbers as low as possible. Now, many of these same institutions worked to unite around Ms. Royal, with considerably less success.

Mr. Le Pen has more than doubled his vote share from five years ago, winning several departments in the northeast and south of the country. He saw particular strength in areas most affected by the ongoing global market crash, although failed to meet expectations in places most affected by the Middle Eastern migrant crisis. Ms. Royal, by contrast, saw considerable success in France’s cities and traditionally left wing southwest. Her numbers were weaker than expected in the northwest, where conservative voters either abstained or backed the far-right Le Pen.

Ms. Royal will enter office with economic trouble and record-high migrant inflows at the top of her agenda. Despite repeated calls on her part for a governing “alliance of the republic,” center-right leaders have stuck to the hardline rhetoric that characterized their campaigns. Much of her success will be dependent on the results in this June’s parliamentary elections. Currently, Ms. Royal’s Socialist Party is polling at 20%, in comparison to 26% for Mr. Le Pen’s National Front.

Soon after the polls closed, a pallid Ms. Royal gave a victory speech at a party gathering that resembled a funeral more than it did a celebration. After thanking the French people for their trust in her, she declared that she “heard their voice” and would work tirelessly to “bring the republic together.” Nearby in Paris, a jubilant Mr. Le Pen, flanked by his daughter, Marine, declared that “this is really just the beginning.”

FROM THE EDITORS; The Times and Iraq

nytimes.com

May 26, 2005

They say that hindsight is 20/20, and over the past year this newspaper has tried on its fair share of prescription glasses. We have taken a close look at the highly flawed intelligence on Saddam Hussein’s weapons capabilities “spun” by members of the Bush administration to support their claims of an imminent threat. We have seen members of the intelligence community come forward and state their concerns over the conclusions on Iraq’s biological weapons program were overruled by supervisors. We have even taken a critical look at the dubious evidence connecting anti-Saddam campaigners to reporters at other journalistic outlets. It is long past time for this newspaper to look inward at its own failures.

In doing so–reviewing thousands of articles published by The Times in the lead-up to the war and since its beginning–we have an enormous amount to be proud of. When other outlets were fixated on conspiracy theories about President George Bush and his administration, we stayed laser-focused on the threat Saddam Hussein posed to the Middle East and to American interests. We remain proud of this work. Some select articles did include flawed or incomplete information, but this is simply how the news business works. We have nothing to apologize for.

However there were some occasions where we relied on inaccurate sources. In a February 2003 piece “U.S. INTEL SAYS HUSSEIN INTENSIFIES QUEST FOR A-BOMB PARTS,” we quoted two senior administration officials and one member of the National Security Council. Our reporter on the piece, Judith Miller, also interviewed four C.I.A. analysts, two United Nations weapons inspectors, and consulted with over a dozen former members of the intelligence community. All came to the same conclusion, based on their years of experience and firsthand knowledge of Saddam’s arsenal: he had no weapons of mass destruction. All quotes and findings from these officials (except the two White House officials) were cut from the final piece for space. We stand by that decision.

In another February 2003 article, headlined “AFRICAN URANIUM LOOTED BY ‘MADMAN’ SADDAM; IRAQI NUCLEAR WARHEAD COULD REACH NEW YORK IN NINE MINUTES; ANTHRAX MAY ALREADY BE IN THE AIR,” some of the wording did not meet our editorial standards. For instance, the line “Saddam’s fanatical quest for nuclear weapons and his lust for power have lured him to an unlikely source: the small African nation of Niger” could have done without the word “fanatical.” Additionally, concerns over possible racial bias in an editorial on Nigerien uranium written by Senator Jeff Sessions (R-AL) were cited. We regret his use of the term “warfare queens.”

We also have heard objections from many readers over the piece published on our website on the day before Congress voted on the resolution to war. This article was erroneously published early online, and did not intend to include Senior White House advisor Karl Rove’s full email address or the correspondence he had with our reporters. We regret any misconceived notions our readers may have come away with, particularly over Rove’s email headlined “FWD: FWD: new DIA slop on saddam-north korea links fr u” and Miller’s response “Great, thank you.” Our reporting process is thorough, and we strongly resent Mr. Rove’s vivid description of the White House “hiking up its skirt” and making sure “our analysis is being printed verbatim on the front page.”

We consider the story of Iraq's weapons, and of the pattern of misinformation, to be unfinished business. And we fully intend to continue aggressive reporting aimed at setting the record straight.

In a generational first, the U.S. has a hung House of Representatives

washingtonpost.com
Thursday, November 6, 2014

The last time one party failed to win majority control of the U.S. House of Representatives, the year was 1916. Woodrow Wilson was President, war was raging in Europe, and the hottest political topics in the country were prohibition, child labor, and women's suffrage. The parties were divided near-evenly in the chamber, with both short of the 218-seat majority by only a few seats. Ultimately, Democrats managed to stay in control through an alliance with Progressive and Socialist members, keeping Speaker Champ Clark in office.

While the political context for this year’s midterm elections nearly a full century later could not be more different, the outcome has been the same. At the start of President Clinton’s term, Republicans were hoping for major gains, similar to those made by themselves in the 2006 midterms and Democrats in the 2002 and 2010 midterms, that would wipe out the small House majority Democrats secured after the 2012 elections. Instead, both parties ended up losing seats to an eclectic group of independents known as the “Teal Bloc,” who grew into a phenomenon across the nation’s college towns and suburbs.

What defines this so-called bloc? While the candidates do not officially coordinate amongst each other, their campaigns had two main themes: support for LGBT rights and advocacy for increased action on climate change. Both of these stances were notable for relating to issues have been absent to the discourse of recent major elections, largely as a result of both parties holding similar stances. All of the four presidents of this century—Bush, Byrd, Santorum and Clinton—have referred to homosexuality as an “abomination” either while in office or on the campaign trail, and all either dismissed or were reluctant to address the risk of climate change.

While many analysts concluded that this was simply politicians recognizing the opinion of middle America and ignoring the insular discourse of coastal elites, it appears as if they were the ones who missed something big. Running as de facto Democratic candidates in some races and full-on third party options against both major parties in a few contests, the Teals found a ready audience across much of the country, with an appeal far from limited to urban enclaves.

Possibly buoyed by a last-minute endorsement from the cast of Modern Family, Teal candidates defeated both Republicans and Democrats across the country, gaining seats from the central Bronx, suburban Orange County, and even rural Iowa. In a particularly dramatic result, it appears as if Teal candidate Douglas Applegate has edged out House Minority Leader Darrel Issa in his Southern California district, ending his chances of becoming Speaker regardless of how negotiations play out in the winter.

Speaking to the press following the results, President Clinton took seemingly great pleasure in chastising reporters on their supposedly unanimous predictions of a red wave, telling them to “think twice” the next time they thought about writing a story on her approval ratings. When asked about how her party was approaching negotiations to strike a governing deal with the Teal bloc, she bristled, remarking that “they” should be asked about how they will “win us over.”

Vox Dot Com: “Absolutely Mandatory Gay Champagne Socialism,” explained

By Jess Fang | January 8, 2016

The Democratic Socialists of America’s Twitter account goes viral for styling former President John Edwards as Ho Chi Minh. A New Yorker podcast asks about what the Manhattan cocktail party circuit can tell us about “class consciousness.” A senior White House aide is spotted carrying a copy of Samuel R. Delany’s Times Square Red, Times Square Blue and Thomas Piketty Capital in the Twenty-First Century into a cabinet meeting.

All of this is to say, the left in America is having a moment. While it’s manifested in big ways and small, its current cultural cachet is nowhere more evident than than the growing ubiquity of the phrase “Absolutely Mandatory Gay Champagne Socialism.”

I’m sorry—Absolutely Mandatory What?

Yes, you read that right. Absolutely Mandatory Gay Champagne Socialism. The label, which most advocates, insist is not completely serious, refers to a belief that all people have a right to have their needs met, where the bottom of Maslow’s hierarchy of needs is lopped off by the state.

In this conception advanced by today’s resurgent left, workers would be free to not just survive but thrive with the fulfilling upper class lifestyle of Eustace Tilley, with opportunities for travel, parties, and, yes, champagne. It would be a world of endless cocktail parties, sexual exploration, and road trips, a sunny utopian world where you would work a minimum number of hours (this is the “Absolutely Mandatory” part of the equation) before being free to pursue whichever leisure activities you desire.

Isn’t Champaign Socialism an epithet?

Indeed, it is! The term “champagne socialist” has traditionally been used as a criticism of left-leaning figures by the right. The phrase has often been meant to mock members of the elite whose wealth and consumption habits appear in conflict with their attitudes on wealth redistribution and similar positions.

Before its modern virality, the phrase was used by the Republican National Committee to attack former President John Edwards, whose wealth appeared in contrast with his left-leaning populist positions.

Where is this coming from?

As Google Trends indicates, the phrase “champagne socialist” gained particular traction between 2004 and 2008, particularly on liberal and other left-leaning internet forums. As Know Your Meme explains:

“The phrase began as a self-deprecating joke, particularly among members of sites like Something Awful. Taking inspiration from right-wing critiques of the White House’s response to the 2006 college tuition protests, many posters began styling themselves as aristocrats or gentry, using their enormous wealth to help John Edwards ‘bring Actually Existing Socialism to Amerikkka.’”


As the phrase spread and as its early advocates became increasingly “irony poisoned,” the self-mocking tone vanished. With the rise of the modern dandyism aesthetic following the financial crash, an increasing number of prominent posters came to adopt it uncritically. All of this coalesced in the anonymously penned “Absolutely Mandatory Gay Champagne Socialism: A Manifesto,” an open source book claiming that universities, theaters, and bookstores could serve as laboratories of leftist and socially liberal ideas.

Who actually believes this?

Depending on who you ask, “Absolutely Mandatory Gay Champagne Socialism” is either a joke poking fun at the absurdity of the growing number of upwardly mobile young people using politics for social capital or it is the secret codex one needs to understand how America operates today.

For the first camp, AMGS is an inside joke for a handful of cultural writers at the New Yorker, New York Magazine, New York Times and other “tastemaker” publications that has gradually disseminated into the broader milieu. These individuals suggest that AMGC is nothing more than a “funny phrase” that speaks to some particular aspects of current political coalitions.

For the second camp, largely consisting of several anonymous and extremely prolific Twitter posters, “champagne socialism” is an ideal to strive for and a platform that leftists should adopt. In the words of one poster, mysteriously retweeted by former President John Edwards, “it’s time to redistribute Hamilton tickets to the masses. voters of the world unite, you have nothing to lose but your Ticketmaster fees.”

Europe Must Come Around on Washington

By Mika Aaltola, Intelligent Life | The Economist
Op-ed, April 12th, 2007

Last month, I was alongside a gaggle of other journalists invited to watch the President of the United States give an address at the Senato de Publica (Senate of the Republic) in Rome, Italy. Now usually it is the other way around, with foreign leaders coming to America to address Congress as a display of international camaraderie, but surprisingly, President Clark has decided to stick it the other way.

With the elegant poise of a general, President Clark would waste no time in addressing the elephant in the room: the specter of Russian influence in Europe. And the agenda was covered concisely with the simple request to the allies of Moscow, stop backing the regime. But this time, the President went a step further.

“Up north, in the Italian heartland, is a small nation that has, regrettably, chosen to align itself with the authoritarians in the Kremlin. Right in your own backyard.”

San Marino, a landlocked enclave nestled within the Italian Peninsula, has traditionally maintained a neutral stance in foreign affairs. Recently however, an uptick in Gazprom investments, such as a cheque for one-hundred-thousand US dollars to reportedly “build a new medical school” display that the Captains Regent in the Palazzo has made his stance clear. To some, President Clark’s directness may come off as ‘brash’ or ‘impulsive’. However, such criticisms fail to grasp the game of geopolitical chess being played by the Clark administration. It is clear that his actions are guided by a deep-seated conviction in the righteousness of the Western cause above all else.

In an article from The Politico that was released just yesterday, a European diplomat, speaking candidly on the condition of anonymity, stated: “What we are seeing is a dangerous game of brinkmanship,” and in that same article, the magazine stated that sources close to Chancellor Merz suggest that he is “pissed off” at the perceived disregard for European interests in the face of American assertiveness.

But the leadership in both Berlin and Brussels must realize that the alternative to Clark is far grimmer. And to Chancellor Merz, I say this: instead of dwelling on perceived slights and petty squabbles over diplomatic protocol, focus on the broader stratagems at hand. Democracy in the western world cannot afford anything else.

In President Clark, we finally have a leader who is not content to stand by and watch as the forces of authoritarianism gather strength against us. Instead, he is leading the charge against tyranny with courage and conviction. Thus reminding us all that the fight for freedom is always one worth fighting.

} return construct(0); } function getTooltips(str) { let matches = []; tooltipList.forEach((tooltip, index) => { // Adjust the regex to match searchString potentially surrounded by “ and followed by optional punctuation let regex = new RegExp(`(?<=\\b|\\s|^|“)${tooltip.searchString}(?=[.,;!?]?\\b|\\s|”|$)`, 'g'); let match; while ((match = regex.exec(str)) !== null) { matches.push({ start: match.index + (match[0].startsWith('“') ? 1 : 0), // Adjust for potential starting “ end: match.index + match[0].length - (match[0].endsWith('”') ? 1 : 0) - (match[2] ? 1 : 0), tooltipIndex: index }); } }); // Sort by starting position; if two start at the same position, longer match comes first matches.sort((a, b) => a.start - b.start || b.end - b.start - (a.end - a.start)); // Filter out overlaps for (let i = 0; i < matches.length - 1; ) { if (matches[i + 1].start < matches[i].end) { matches.splice(i + 1, 1); // Remove the next match since it overlaps } else { i++; // Move to next match } } return matches; } function applyTooltips(str) { const matches = getTooltips(str); let result = ''; let lastIndex = 0; matches.forEach(match => { const tooltip = tooltipList[match.tooltipIndex]; result += str.slice(lastIndex, match.start); result += `${tooltip.searchString}${tooltip.explanationText}`; lastIndex = match.end; }); result += str.slice(lastIndex); // Add the remainder of the original string return result; } function applyTooltipsToObject(obj) { for (let key in obj) { if (typeof obj[key] === 'string') { obj[key] = applyTooltips(obj[key]); } else if (typeof obj[key] === 'object') { applyTooltipsToObject(obj[key]); // Recursive call } } } applyTooltipsToObject(campaignTrail_temp.questions_json); applyTooltipsToObject(campaignTrail_temp.answers_json); applyTooltipsToObject(campaignTrail_temp.answer_feedback_json);
